 them to learn all about bulldozers and other construction vehicles and how they work through song. \n\n3. Fire Truck Songs\n\nDuring an open house at the fire department, two kids meet Freddy the Friendly Fire Engine as they embark on a musical journey learning all about fire trucks. Along the way, the kids learn about the various types of tools and equipment the firefighters use as well as various fire safety guidelines. Various songs are used to entertain the kids.\n\n4. Santa Songs\n\nAn animated [[Santa Claus]] takes the viewers on a holiday musical adventure.\n\n==DVD releases==\n{{Expand section|date=October 2018}}\nThe \"Real Wheels\" series has also released a series of DVD, each usually containing two episodes as well as a blooper reel, interactive glossary, and other special features. The DVDs are usually titled as \"Adventures\", with three episodes sharing a theme among their featured vehicles. A spin-off called \"Rockin' Real Wheels\" was also released featuring songs about a specific type of vehicle. All episodes except for Here Comes a Roller Coaster, There Goes Santa Claus, and Santa Songs were featured on DVD.\n\n===\"Adventures\" DVDs===\n1. Truck Adventures\n\nThere Goes a Fire Truck, There Goes a Garbage Truck, and There Goes a Truck.\n\n2. Mega Truck Adventures\n\nThere Goes a Bulldozer, There Goes a Monster Truck, and There Goes a Tank.\n\n3. High Speed Adventures\n\nThere Goes a Race Car, There Goes a Motorcycle, and There Goes a Spaceship.\n\n4. Travel Adventures\n\nThere Goes a Train, There Goes a Plane, and There Goes a Bus.\n\n5. Land, Sea, and Air Adventures\n\nThere Goes a Boat, There Goes the Mail, and There Goes a Helicopter.\n\n6. Tractor Adventures\n\nThere Goes a Tractor, There Goes a Dump Truck, and There Goes a Farm Truck.\n\n7. Rescue Adventures\n\nThere Goes a Rescue Hero, There Goes a Police Car, and There Goes a Rescue Vehicle.\n\n8. Rockin' Real Wheels\n\nTrain Songs, Bulldozer Songs, and Fire Truck Songs.\n\n==Reception==\nThe ''Real Wheels'' series had over 8 million dollars in sales and had won numerous awards including the Dove Foundation Award, The National Parenting Association Award, the [[Parents' Choice Award]], and Kid's First Endorsement Award.\n\n==Live tour==\n\nFrom 2001-2004, there was a live tour entitled, \"Dave's Big Live Show\" (aka Real Wheels Live). It starred [[Dave Hood]] that featured him doing magic tricks and had audience participation stunts. Before the show, there were vehicles that the audience would touch and look at. \n\nThe production was produced and presented by Dave Hood Entertainment.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1990s American children's television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American children's television series]]\n[[Category:1993 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2003 American television series endings]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: Tuscon \u2192 Tucson", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/There_Goes_a..."}
{"title_page": "Cerro Blanco (volcano)", "text_new": "{{dablinks|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name=Cerro Blanco\n| photo = Cerro Blanco volcano (AVA Granule L1B 20000916145757).jpg\n| photo_alt =Optical satellite image of Cerro Blanco caldera and the Piedra Pomez ignimbrite\n| photo_caption = Satellite image of Cerro Blanco volcano. The black area on the upper edge is Carachipampa volcano. Cerro Blanco caldera is located slightly left and below the centre of the image and is the gray-yellow area.\n| location = [[Catamarca Province]], [[Argentina]]\n| range = [[Andes]]\n| map = Argentina |relief=1\n|range_coordinates = \n| map_size = 175\n| map_caption = Location in Argentina\n| label_position = right\n|coordinates = {{coord|26|45|37|S|67|44|29|W|type:mountain_region:AR_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_ref = <ref name=GVP />\n| elevation_m= 4670\n| elevation_ft= 15318\n| elevation_ref=<ref name=GVP />|map_alt = Cerro Blanco is located in northwestern Argentina|map_relief = |listing = [[List of volcanoes in Argentina]]|translation = White Mountain|language = Spanish|type = [[Caldera]]|age = [[Holocene]]|volcanic_belt = [[Central Volcanic Zone]]|last_eruption = 2,300 \u00b1 160 BCE<ref name=GVP />}}\n'''Cerro Blanco''' is a [[caldera]] in the [[Andes]] of the [[Catamarca Province]] in [[Argentina]]. Part of the [[Central Volcanic Zone]] of the Andes, it is a volcano collapse structure located at an altitude of {{convert|4670|m}} in a depression. The caldera is associated with a less well defined caldera to the south and several [[lava dome]]s.\n\nThe caldera has been active for the last eight million years and eruptions have created several [[ignimbrite]]s. A recent eruption occurred 73,000 years ago and formed the Campo de la Piedra P\u00f3mez ignimbrite layer. About 2,300 \u00b1 160 BCE,<ref name=GVP /> the largest volcanic eruption of the Central Andes with a [[volcanic explosivity index|VEI]] 7 occurred at Cerro Blanco, forming the most recent caldera as well as thick ignimbrite layers. Over {{convert|170|km3}} of [[tephra]] were erupted then. The volcano is dormant since then with some deformation and geothermal activity. A major future eruption would put local communities to the south at risk.\n\nThe volcano is also known for giant [[ripple marks]] that have formed on its ignimbrite fields. Persistent wind action on the ground has shifted gravel and sand, forming wave-like structures. These ripple marks have heights up to {{convert|1|m}} and are separated by distances up to {{convert|30|m}}. Unlike [[dune]]s, they do not migrate with the wind and are stationary. These ripple marks are among the most extreme on Earth and have been compared to [[Mars|Martian]] ripple marks by geologists.\n\n== Geography and geomorphology ==\n\nThe caldera lies at the southern margin of the Argentine [[Altiplano|Puna]]{{efn|The [[Altiplano]]-Puna is the second-largest [[high plateau]] on Earth after the [[Tibetan Plateau]] and consists of a number of [[mountain range]]s separated by valleys with [[closed drainage]].{{sfn|Montero L\u00f3pez|Hongn|Seggiaro|Marrett|2009|p=138}} }},{{sfn|Kay|Coira|Mpodozis|2006|p=499}} on the border between the [[Antofagasta de la Sierra Department]] and the [[Tinogasta Department]]{{sfn|Ratto|Rodr\u00edguez Gonz\u00e1lez|Basile|P\u00e9rez Torrado|2018|p=76}} in the [[Catamarca Province]] of Argentina.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=3}} [[Trail]]s run through the area,{{sfn|Milana|2009|p=343}} and there are abandoned [[mining]] operations.{{sfn|Milana|2009|p=344}} [[Provincial Route 34 (Catamarca)]] between [[Fiambal\u00e1]] and [[Antofagasta de la Sierra]] runs past Cerro Blanco.{{sfn|Montero L\u00f3pez|Hongn|Seggiaro|Marrett|2009|p=140}} The volcano is sometimes known as Cerro Blanco and sometimes as Robledo,{{sfn|Pritchard|Simons|2004|p=10}} with the latter name used by the [[Smithsonian Institution]].{{sfn|Brunori|Bignami|Stramondo|Bustos|2013|p=279}}\n\n=== Calderas and lava domes ===\n\nCerro Blanco lies at an elevation of {{convert|3500|-|4700|m}} and consists of four nested calderas{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|pp=4-5}} with discontinuous borders,{{sfn|Seggiaro|Hongn|Castillo|Pereyra|2006|p=27}} fallout deposits, [[lava dome]]s{{sfn|Brunori|Bignami|Stramondo|Bustos|2013|p=281}} and [[pyroclastic]] deposits.{{sfn|Chiodi|Tassi|B\u00e1ez|Filipovich|2019|p=2}} The two inconspicuous El Ni\u00f1o and Pie de San Buenaventura calderas are nested in the northern part of the complex{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|pp=4-5}} and form a {{convert|15|km}} wide depression.{{sfn|Montero L\u00f3pez|Hongn|Seggiaro|Marrett|2009|p=140}} Only their northern margins are recognizable in satellite images; their southern parts are filled with [[block and ash flow]]s from the southern calderas. The southern calderas are the Robledo and Cerro Blanco calderas, which form a southeast-northwest trending pair.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|pp=4-5}} Alternative interpretations consider the Pie de San Buenaventura, Robledo and Cerro Blanco calderas as one {{convert|13|x|10|km}} caldera,{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=Litosoma 2: Caldera del Cerro Blanco}} that the Robledo and Cerro Blanco calderas are one system{{sfn|Brunori|Bignami|Stramondo|Bustos|2013|p=285}} or envisage the existence of only three calderas.{{sfn|Seggiaro|Hongn|Castillo|Pereyra|2006|p=27}}\n\nThe Cerro Blanco caldera is about {{convert|6|km}}<ref name=\"GVP\" />-{{convert|4|km}} wide and its walls are up to {{convert|300|m}} high.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Bustos|Chiodi|Reckziegel|2020|p=3}} They are formed by ignimbrite [[breccia]], ignimbrites and lava domes cut by the caldera margins.{{sfn|Kay|Coira|Mpodozis|2008|p=154}} The caldera floor is almost entirely covered by block-and-ash flows, apart from an area where [[hydrothermal]] activity has left white [[Siliceous sinter|sinter]] deposits.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=25}} A slight circular uplift on the caldera floor may be a [[cryptodome]].{{sfn|Seggiaro|Hongn|Castillo|Pereyra|2006|p=31}} \n\nThe caldera has an almost perfectly circular outline with the exception of the southwestern margin{{sfn|Seggiaro|Hongn|Castillo|Pereyra|2006|p=27}} which is cut by a {{convert|2.7|x|1.4|km}} wide [[lava dome]].{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=14}} This dome is also known as Cerro Blanco{{sfn|Montero L\u00f3pez|Hongn|Affonso Brod|Seggiaro|2010|loc=Complejo Volc\u00e1nico Cerro Blanco}} or Cerro Blanco del Robledo<ref name=\"GVP\" /> and reaches a height of {{convert|4697|m}} above sea level.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|2019|p=6}} Three additional lava domes surround this dome, and an [[explosion crater]] lies to its southwest. West of this crater{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Chiodi|Bustos|Arnosio|2016|p=226}} there are three pinkish lava domes{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=14}} lined up in west-southwest direction away from the main dome;{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=5}} these are surrounded by [[pyroclastic cone]]s{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Chiodi|Bustos|Arnosio|2016|p=226}} and depressions.{{sfn|Montero L\u00f3pez|Hongn|Affonso Brod|Seggiaro|2010|loc=Complejo Volc\u00e1nico Cerro Blanco}}\n\nOwing to erosion, the Robledo caldera{{sfn|Seggiaro|Hongn|Castillo|Pereyra|2006|p=28}} is less well defined than the Cerro Blanco caldera.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=Litosoma 2: Caldera del Cerro Blanco}} A site southeast of the Robledo caldera is known as Robledo.{{sfn|Brunori|Bignami|Stramondo|Bustos|2013|p=270}} South of the Robledo caldera lies the Portezuelo de Robledo [[mountain pass]]{{sfn|Montero L\u00f3pez|Hongn|Affonso Brod|Seggiaro|2010|loc=Complejo Volc\u00e1nico Cerro Blanco}} and the south-eastward trending El M\u00e9dano plain.{{sfn|Chiodi|Tassi|B\u00e1ez|Filipovich|2019|p=2}}\n\n{{convert|8|km}} northeast of Cerro Blanco lies a {{convert|1.2|km}} wide and {{convert|20|m}} deep vent known as El Escondido{{sfn|Montero L\u00f3pez|Hongn|Affonso Brod|Seggiaro|2010|loc=Complejo Volc\u00e1nico Cerro Blanco}} or El Oculto.{{sfn|Chiodi|Tassi|B\u00e1ez|Filipovich|2019|p=2}} It does not have a strong topographic expression but is conspicuous on satellite images as a semi-circular patch of darker material.{{sfn|Montero L\u00f3pez|Hongn|Affonso Brod|Seggiaro|2010|loc=Complejo Volc\u00e1nico Cerro Blanco}} [[Gravimetric]] analysis has found a number of gravity anomalies around the caldera.{{sfn|Di Filippo|Di Nezza|Colombi|Viramonte|2008|p=204}}\n\n=== Surrounding terrain ===\n\nThe terrain northeast-east from Cerro Blanco is covered by its ignimbrites and by [[Plinian eruption|Plinian]] fallout deposits{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Chiodi|Bustos|Arnosio|2016|p=224}} which radiate away from the calderas.{{sfn|Seggiaro|Hongn|Castillo|Pereyra|2006|p=27}} Cerro Blanco lies at the southwestern end of the Carachipampa valley,{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Bustos|Chiodi|Reckziegel|2020|p=2}} a volcano-tectonic depression flanked by [[normal fault]]s which extends to Carachipampa. This depression appears to have formed in response to north-south tectonic extension of the Puna{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=Litosoma 1: Depresi\u00f3n volcano-tect\u00f3nica Campo de la Piedra P\u00f3mez}} and is covered by volcanic deposits from Cerro Blanco.{{sfn|Chiodi|Tassi|B\u00e1ez|Filipovich|2019|p=2}} These volcanic deposits form the \"Campo de Pedra Pomez\"{{sfn|Seggiaro|Hongn|Castillo|Pereyra|2006|loc=Mapa}} and extend {{convert|50|km}} away from the volcano.{{sfn|Montero L\u00f3pez|Hongn|Seggiaro|Marrett|2009|p=142}}\n\nOther valleys are the Purulla valley northwest from Cerro Blanco and Incahuasi due north; all three contain both volcanic deposits from Cerro Blanco and [[salt pan (geology)|salt flats]]{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Bustos|Chiodi|Reckziegel|2020|p=2}} or lakes.{{sfn|Kay|Coira|Mpodozis|2008|p=163}} In the Incahuasi valley an ignimbrite also known as the \"white ignimbrite\" reaches a distance of over {{convert|25|km}}.{{sfn|Kay|Coira|Mpodozis|2008|p=154}} Wind has carved up to {{convert|20|-|25|m}} deep channels into the ignimbrites.{{sfn|Milana|Forman|Kr\u00f6hling|2010|p=219}}\n\n=== Aeolian landscapes ===\n\nOne of the most spectacular [[aeolian processes|aeolian]] landscapes of Earth is found at Cerro Blanco,{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Bustos|Chiodi|Reckziegel|2020|p=2}} where large wind-formed [[ripple mark]]s occur.{{sfn|Milana|2009|p=343}} These ripples cover Cerro Blanco ignimbrites{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Bustos|Chiodi|Reckziegel|2020|pp=9-10}} and reach heights of {{convert|2.3|m}} and wavelengths of {{convert|43|m}}, making them the largest ripples known on Earth and comparable to similar ripple fields on [[Mars]].{{sfn|Milana|2009|p=343}} Wind-driven erosion of ignimbrites{{efn|The source rocks for the ripples include both older volcanic rocks and rocks erupted by Cerro Blanco, with different main components in different areas.{{sfn|Silva|Spagnuolo|Bridges|Zimbelman|2013|p=1913}}}} has generated the ripples,<ref name=\"Silva2010\" /> which consist of gravel, pebbles and sand{{sfn|Milana|2009|p=344}} and are covered with gravel{{sfn|Silva|Spagnuolo|Bridges|Zimbelman|2013|p=1912}} Smaller [[gravel]]ly ripples lie atop the larger ripples and troughs{{sfn|Milana|2009|p=343}} and there are intermediate sized forms ({{convert|0.6|-|0.8|m}} high); they may be precursors to the large ripples and make up most of the ripples in the fields.{{sfn|Milana|2009|p=344}} Their wind-driven movement is fast enough that trails abandoned four years before are already partly covered with them.{{sfn|Milana|2009|p=344}}  \n\nThe ripple marks cover areas of about {{convert|150|km2}} or {{convert|600|km2}} in the Carachipampa and {{convert|80|km2}} or {{convert|127|km2}} in the Purulla{{efn|The Purulla valley{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Bustos|Chiodi|Reckziegel|2020|p=2}} appears to be the same valley as the Puruya valley.{{sfn|Milana|2009|p=343}}}} valley, where a field of large ripples covers an area of {{convert|8|km2}}{{sfn|Silva|Spagnuolo|Bridges|Zimbelman|2013|p=1913}}{{sfn|Milana|2009|p=343}} and is accompanied by [[yardang]]s; this field is also the place where the largest ripples occur.{{sfn|Milana|2009|p=344}} \n\nVarious wind-dependent mechanisms have been proposed to explain their large size, including the presence of [[roll vortex]]es, [[Kelvin\u2013Helmholtz instability|Helmholtz instability]]-like phenomena, atmospheric [[gravity wave]]s{{sfn|Milana|2009|p=346}} or [[Downhill creep|creep]]-like movement when pumice fragments and sand are lifted from the ground by wind and fall back.{{sfn|Silva|Spagnuolo|Bridges|Zimbelman|2013|p=1919}} The latter view envisages that undulating terrain triggers the development of ripples through the accumulation of gravel and sand at such undulations.{{sfn|Silva|Spagnuolo|Bridges|Zimbelman|2013|p=1926}} Their formation appears to be influenced by whether the rock material available can be moved by wind{{sfn|Milana|2009|p=345}} while a role of the bedrock structure or the size of the rocks is controversial.{{sfn|Milana|Forman|Kr\u00f6hling|2010|p=220}}<ref name=\"Silva2010\" />\n\n[[File:Campo de Piedra P\u00f3mez, Catamarca, Argentina.jpg|thumbnail|Campo de Piedra P\u00f3mez yardangs]]\nWind has also formed demoiselles and [[yardang]]s in the ignimbrites.{{sfn|Silva|Spagnuolo|Bridges|Zimbelman|2013|p=1913}} These are particularly well expressed in the Campo de Piedra Pomez area{{sfn|Aulinas|Garcia-Valles|Fernandez-Turiel|Gimeno|2015|p=449}} southeast of the Carachipampa valley,{{sfn|Aulinas|Garcia-Valles|Fernandez-Turiel|Gimeno|2015|p=448}} a {{convert|25|x|5|km}} area where yardangs, [[hoodoo (geology)|hoodoo]]s and wind-exposed cliffs create a majestic landscape. The structures reach widths of {{convert|2|-|20|m}}.{{sfn|Aulinas|Garcia-Valles|Fernandez-Turiel|Gimeno|2015|p=449}} Exposed rocks are often covered with brown, orange or beige [[desert varnish]].{{sfn|Aulinas|Garcia-Valles|Fernandez-Turiel|Gimeno|2015|p=450}}\n\n=== Regional ===\n\nCerro Blanco is located south of the southern end of the Filo Colorado{{sfn|Brunori|Bignami|Stramondo|Bustos|2013|p=280}}/Los Colorados mountain range{{sfn|Chiodi|Tassi|B\u00e1ez|Filipovich|2019|p=2}} and at eastern end of the Cordillera de San Buenaventura.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=4}} The Cordillera de San Buenaventura marks the southern margin of the Puna{{sfn|Montero L\u00f3pez|Hongn|Affonso Brod|Seggiaro|2010|loc=INTRODUCCI\u00d3N}} and extends west-southwestwards from Cerro Blanco to the volcanoes [[Nevado San Francisco|San Francisco]] and [[Falso Azufre]]{{sfn|Kay|Coira|Mpodozis|2008|p=163}} and the [[Paso de San Francisco]].{{sfn|Seggiaro|Hongn|Castillo|Pereyra|2006|loc=Mapa}}  \n\nA series of 6-1 million years old{{sfn|Seggiaro|Hongn|Castillo|Pereyra|2006|p=39}} [[andesitic]] to [[dacitic]] [[stratovolcano]]es make up the Cordillera de San Buenaventura,{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Chiodi|Bustos|Arnosio|2016|p=225}} and [[Quaternary]] [[basalt]]ic volcanoes are dispersed over the wider region.{{sfn|Chiodi|Tassi|B\u00e1ez|Filipovich|2019|p=2}} In the surroundings of Cerro Blanco lies the [[Cueros de Purulla]] volcano {{convert|25|km}} north and the [[Nevado Tres Cruces]]-[[El Solo]]-[[Ojos del Salado]] complex farther west.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=4}}\n\n== Geology ==\n\n[[Subduction]] of the [[Nazca Plate]] beneath the [[South America Plate]] occurs in the [[Peru-Chile Trench]] at a rate of {{convert|6.7|cm/year|in/year}}. It is responsible for the volcanism in the Andes, which is localized in three volcanic zones known as the [[Northern Volcanic Zone]], [[Central Volcanic Zone]] and [[Southern Volcanic Zone]].{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Bustos|Chiodi|Reckziegel|2020|p=2}} Cerro Blanco is part of the Andean [[Central Volcanic Zone]] (CVZ), and one of its southernmost volcanoes.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=3}} The CVZ is sparsely inhabited and recent volcanic activity is only poorly recorded;{{sfn|Pritchard|Simons|2004|p=2}} [[Lascar (volcano)|Lascar]] is the only regularly active volcano there.<ref name=\"SCN24\" />\n\nThe CVZ extends over the [[Altiplano]]-Puna{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=3}} where [[calc-alkaline]] volcanism has been ongoing since the [[Miocene]].{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=4}} Characteristic for the CVZ are the large fields of [[Ignimbrite|ignimbritic]] volcanism and associated [[caldera]]s, chiefly in the [[Altiplano-Puna volcanic complex]]. In the southern part of the CVZ such volcanic systems are usually small and are poorly studied.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=INTRODUCCI\u00d3N}} During the [[Neogene]], volcanism commenced in the [[Maricunga belt]] and eventually shifted to its present-day location in the [[Cordillera Occidental (Bolivia)|Western Cordillera]].{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Bustos|Chiodi|Reckziegel|2020|p=3}} Tectonic processes also took place, such as two phases of east-west compression; the first was in the middle [[Miocene]] and the second began 7 million years ago.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=MARCO GEOL\u00d3GICO}}\n\nVolcanism in the southern Puna region initiated about 8 million years ago and took place in several stages, which were characterized by the emplacement of [[lava dome]]s and of [[ignimbrite]]s such as the 4.0 - 3.7 million years old [[Laguna Amarga]]-Laguna Verde ignimbrites. Some of the domes are located close to the border with Chile in the [[Ojos del Salado]] and [[Nevado Tres Cruces]] area. Later there also were [[mafic]] eruptions, which generated lava flows in the Carachipampa and Laguna de Purulla area.{{sfn|Kay|Coira|Mpodozis|2006|p=500}} From the [[Miocene]] to the [[Pliocene]] the [[La Hoyada volcanic complex]] was active{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=4}} southwest of Cerro Blanco;{{sfn|Montero L\u00f3pez|Hongn|Affonso Brod|Seggiaro|2010|loc=Figura 2}} afterwards came a 2 million years long hiatus.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=RESULTADOS: ESTRATIGRAF\u00cdA DEL CVCB}} Cerro Blanco overlies this volcanic complex{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=4}} and outcrops of La Hoyada are found inside{{sfn|Seggiaro|Hongn|Castillo|Pereyra|2006|p=18}} and around the calderas.{{sfn|Seggiaro|Hongn|Castillo|Pereyra|2006|p=19}}\n\nThe [[basement (geology)|basement]] is formed by [[metamorphic]] and sedimentary rocks of [[Paleozoic]] to [[Mesozoic]] age.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=4}} The former are particularly represented east of Cerro Blanco and go back in part to the [[Precambrian]], the latter occur mainly west and consist of [[Ordovician]] volcano-sedimentary units. Both are intruded by [[granitoid]]s and [[mafic]] and [[ultramafic]] rocks. [[Permian]] sediments and [[Paleogene]] rocks complete the nonvolcanic geology.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=MARCO GEOL\u00d3GICO}} Local tectonic structures{{sfn|Kay|Coira|Mpodozis|2006|p=501}} such as borders between [[crust (geology)|crust]]al domains{{sfn|Guzm\u00e1n|Grosse|Montero-L\u00f3pez|Hongn|2014|p=183}} and northeast-southwest trending [[fault (geology)|fault]]s might control the position of volcanic vents.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=\u00c9poca eruptiva Campo de la Piedra P\u00f3mez}} Tectonic processes may also be responsible for the elliptic shape of the Cerro Blanco caldera.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=Litosoma 2: Caldera del Cerro Blanco}} There is evidence of [[Quaternary]] intense [[earthquakes]]{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=\u00c9poca eruptiva Campo de la Piedra P\u00f3mez}} and some faults such as the El Pe\u00f1\u00f3n Fault have [[neotectonic|been recently active]].{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=Sintema Cortaderas}} \n\n=== Composition ===\n\nMost of the volcanic rocks found at Cerro Blanco are [[rhyolite]]s.{{sfn|Guzm\u00e1n|Grosse|Montero-L\u00f3pez|Hongn|2014|p=186}}{{sfn|Montero L\u00f3pez|Hongn|Affonso Brod|Seggiaro|2010|loc=Elementos mayoritarios}} Minerals encountered in the volcanic rocks include [[biotite]], [[feldspar]], [[ilmenite]], [[magnetite]] [[quartz]], less commonly [[amphibole]], [[clinopyroxene]], [[orthopyroxene]], and rarely [[apatite]], [[allanite]]-[[epidote]], [[muscovite]], [[titanite]] and [[zircon]].{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=7}} Fumarolic alteration on the caldera ground has produced [[alunite]], [[boehmite]] and [[kaolinite]] and deposited [[opal]], [[quartz]] and [[silica]].{{sfn|Chiodi|Tassi|B\u00e1ez|Filipovich|2019|p=3}} \n\nMagma temperatures have been estimated to range between {{convert|600|-|820|C}}. The rhyolites erupted at Cerro Blanco appear to form from [[andesite]] magmas, through processes such as [[fractional crystallization (geology)|fractional crystallization]] and the absorption of [[crust (geology)|crust]]al materials.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Bustos|Chiodi|Reckziegel|2020|p=3}}\n\n== Climate and vegetation ==\n\nMean temperatures in the region are below {{convert|0|C}} but daily temperature fluctuations can reach {{convert|30|C-change}} and [[insolation]] is intense.{{sfn|Aulinas|Garcia-Valles|Fernandez-Turiel|Gimeno|2015|p=449}} Vegetation in the region is classified as a high desert vegetation.{{sfn|Aulinas|Garcia-Valles|Fernandez-Turiel|Gimeno|2015|p=449}} It is bushy and relatively sparse, with thicker plant growth found at hot springs{{sfn|Chiodi|Tassi|B\u00e1ez|Filipovich|2019|p=4}} and in the craters where humid soils occur, perhaps wetted by ascending vapour.{{sfn|Conde Serra|2016|p=4}}\n\nAnnual precipitation is less than {{convert|200|mm/year|in/year}}<ref name=\"Guzm\u00e1n2017\" /> and moisture in the region comes from the [[Amazon basin|Amazon]] in the east.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=24}} The climate of the region has been [[arid]] since the [[Miocene]] but fluctuations in humidity occurred especially during the [[last glacial]]{{sfn|Montero L\u00f3pez|Hongn|Seggiaro|Marrett|2009|p=138}} and between 9,000 - 5,000 years ago when climate was wetter.{{sfn|Montero L\u00f3pez|Hongn|Seggiaro|Marrett|2009|p=151}} The aridity results in a good preservation of volcanic products.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=14}} \n\nStrong winds blow at Cerro Blanco.{{sfn|Silva|Spagnuolo|Bridges|Zimbelman|2013|p=1913}} Average windspeeds are unknown{{sfn|Milana|2009|p=344}} but [[Wind gust|gust]]s of {{convert|20|-|30|m/s}} have been recorded in July<ref name=\"Silva2010\" /> and wind speeds in early December 2010 regularly exceeded {{convert|33|km/h|m/s|order=flip}}.{{sfn|Silva|Spagnuolo|Bridges|Zimbelman|2013|p=1916}} Winds blow mainly from the northwest,{{sfn|Silva|Spagnuolo|Bridges|Zimbelman|2013|p=1913}} and have been stable in that orientation for the past 2 million years. This favoured the development of extensive [[aeolian landform]]s.{{sfn|Aulinas|Garcia-Valles|Fernandez-Turiel|Gimeno|2015|p=455}} Winds kick up pyroclastic material, generating [[dust storm]]s{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Bustos|Chiodi|Reckziegel|2020|p=2}} which remove dust and sand from the area. Some of the dust is carried out into the [[Pampa]], where it forms [[loess]] deposits.{{sfn|Milana|2009|p=343}} [[Dust devil]]s have been observed.<ref name=\"Lorenz2016\" />\n\n== Eruption history ==\n\nThe Cerro Blanco volcanic system has been active during the [[Pleistocene]] and [[Holocene]].{{sfn|Conde Serra|2016|p=3}} The oldest{{efn|The 6.3 \u00b1 0.2 million years old Rosada Ignimbrite may have originated in the area of Cerro Blanco.{{sfn|Seggiaro|Hongn|Castillo|Pereyra|2006|p=23}} It has been hypothesized that the Aguada Alumbrera Ignimbrite, which crops out south of Cerro Blanco, might also have originated there.{{sfn|Montero L\u00f3pez|Hongn|Affonso Brod|Seggiaro|2010|loc=DISCUSI\u00d3N}}}} volcanic rocks related to Cerro Blanco are the over 750,000 years old so-called \"Cortaderas Synthem\", which only crops out close to Laguna Carachipampa. It consists of two ignimbrites, the Barranca Blanca Ignimbrite and the Carachi Ignimbrite, which were erupted a long time apart. The former is a massive, white, unwelded ignimbrite, the latter is massive, rose-coloured and weakly welded. They contain [[pumice]] and fragments of country rock{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=Sintema Cortaderas}} and consist of [[rhyodacite]] unlike later units.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Chiodi|Bustos|Arnosio|2016|p=225}} These ignimbrites, whose chronological relation to each other is unknown, were probably produced by \"boil-over\" of a volcanic vent rather than by an eruption column.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=\u00c9poca eruptiva Cortaderas}} Their exact source vent is unknown.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Chiodi|Bustos|Arnosio|2016|p=225}} \n\nThe Campo de la Piedra P\u00f3mez Ignimbrite covers an area of about {{convert|250|km2}} north of Cerro Blanco and has a volume of about {{convert|17|km3}}. It was emplaced in two units a short time from each other. They both contain pumice and fragments of country rock, similar to the Cortaderas Synthem. The most reliable [[radiometric dating|radiometrically obtained dates]] for this ignimbrite indicate an age of 73,000 years;{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=Sintema Campo de la Piedra P\u00f3mez (SCPP)}} older estimates of their age are 560,000 \u00b1 110,000 and 440,000 \u00b1 10,000 years before present.{{sfn|Guzm\u00e1n|Grosse|Montero-L\u00f3pez|Hongn|2014|p=186}} The eruption reached level 6 on the [[Volcanic Explosivity Index|volcanic explosivity index]]{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=\u00cdndice de explosividad volc\u00e1nica de las erupciones del CVCB}} and is also known as the first cycle ignimbrite.{{sfn|Guzm\u00e1n|Grosse|Montero-L\u00f3pez|Hongn|2014|p=176}} The source vent for this eruption has not been found, there is no agreement whether the Robledo Caldera is the source and the volcano-tectonic depression northeast of Cerro Blanco has been proposed as a source.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=Litosoma 1: Depresi\u00f3n volcano-tect\u00f3nica Campo de la Piedra P\u00f3mez}} As with the Cortaderas Synthem, this ignimbrite was produced by a boiling-over vent and the pyroclastic flows lacked the intensity to override local topography. It is possible that the eruption proceeded in two phases, with a magmatic reinvigoration of the system between the two.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=\u00c9poca eruptiva Campo de la Piedra P\u00f3mez}} After the ignimbrite cooled and solidified, cracks formed in the rocks and were later eroded by wind.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=Sintema Campo de la Piedra P\u00f3mez (SCPP)}} The Robledo and Pie de San Buenaventura calderas were formed during the early activity.{{sfn|Seggiaro|Hongn|Castillo|Pereyra|2006|p=28}}{{sfn|Montero L\u00f3pez|Hongn|Seggiaro|Marrett|2009|p=141}} \n\nThe volcano appears to have erupted repeatedly during the [[Holocene]].{{sfn|Ratto|Montero|Hongn|2013|p=62}}{{sfn|Montero L\u00f3pez|Hongn|Seggiaro|Marrett|2009|p=151}} [[Explosive eruption]]s took place between 8,830 \u00b1 60 and 5,480 \u00b1 40 years [[before present]] and deposited tephra{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Bustos|Chiodi|Reckziegel|2020|p=4}} and [[ignimbrite]]s south of Cerro Blanco.{{sfn|Montero L\u00f3pez|Hongn|Seggiaro|Marrett|2009|p=147}} [[Sulfur oxide]] gases from recent activity at Cerro Blanco may have degraded [[rock painting]]s in the Salamanca cave, {{convert|70|km}} south of the volcano.<ref name=\"Tomasini2012\" />\n\n=== 4.2 ka eruption ===\n\nA large eruption occurred approximately 4200 years ago. Block-and-ash flow deposits (classified as \"CB{{sub|1}}\"{{efn|CB{{sub|1}} is considered to be pre-caldera, CB{{sub|2}} as syn-caldera and CB{{sub|3}} as post-caldera.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=21}}}}) found around the caldera have been interpreted as indicating that a [[lava dome]] was erupted prior to the caldera collapse at Cerro Blanco, although it is not clear by how much this eruption predates the main eruption.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=23}} Deposits from this lava dome-forming episode consist of blocks which sometimes exceed sizes of {{convert|1|m}} embedded within ash and lapilli.{{efn|[[Tephra]] is fragmented rock that is produced by volcanic eruptions. Such fallout is termed \"[[lapilli]]\" when it has a thickness of {{convert|2|-|64|mm}} and \"[[volcanic ash|ash]]\" with less than {{convert|2|mm}} thickness.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=2}}}}{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=6}} \n\nA vent opened up, presumably on the southwestern side of the future caldera, and generated a {{convert|27|km}} high [[eruption column]].{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=23}} [[Fissure vent]]s may have opened as well.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Bustos|Chiodi|Reckziegel|2020|p=13}} After an initial, unstable phase during which alternating layers of [[lapilli]] and [[volcanic ash]] (unit \"CB{{sub|2}}1\") fell out{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=23}} and covered the previous topography,{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=6}} a more steady column deposited thicker [[rhyolitic]] tephra layers (unit \"CB{{sub|2}}2\").{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=23}} At this time, a change in rock composition occurred, perhaps due to new magma entering the [[magma chamber]].{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=25}} \n\nWindy conditions dispersed most of the tephra to the east-southeast,{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=21}} covering a surface of about {{convert|500000|km2}} with about {{convert|170|km3}} of tephra.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=26}} The thickness of the tephra decreases{{efn|A thicker region is found at [[Taf\u00ed del Valle]]{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=13}} {{convert|200|km}} away from Cerro Blanco, where tephra reaches thicknesses of over {{convert|3|m}};{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=6}} climatological factors may have induced a thicker fallout there.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=24}}}} eastward away from Cerro Blanco{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=13}} and reaches a thickness of about {{convert|20|cm}}{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=6}} {{convert|370|km}} away from Cerro Blanco in [[Santiago del Estero]].{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=7}} The tephra deposits in the [[Valles Calchaquies]] and [[Tafi del Valle]] area are known as mid-Holocene ash, Ash C, Buey Muerto ash, and V1 ash layer,{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=22}} and it has been found northeast of [[Antofagasta de la Sierra]].<ref name=\"Grana2016\" /> The tephra from the 4.2 ka eruption has been used as a chronological marker in the region.{{sfn|Ratto|Rodr\u00edguez Gonz\u00e1lez|Basile|P\u00e9rez Torrado|2018|p=82}} Modelling suggests the tephra might have reached [[Brazil]] and [[Paraguay]] farther east.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|2019|p=27}} Close to the vent, tephra fallout was emplaced on the Cordillera de San Buenaventura.{{sfn|Montero L\u00f3pez|Hongn|Seggiaro|Marrett|2009|p=144}} Some of the tephra deposits close to the caldera have been buried by sediments, or [[soil]] development has set in.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=6}} Wind removed the volcanic ash, leaving block and lapilli sized pebbles that cover most of the deposits; in some places dunes have formed from pebbles.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=Sintema Cerro Blanco (SCB)}}\n\n[[Pyroclastic flow]]s also formed, perhaps through instability of the eruption column (unit \"CB{{sub|2}}3\"),{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=25}} and spread away from the volcano through surrounding valleys. They reached distances of {{convert|35|km}} from Cerro Blanco{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=8}} and while many of their up to {{convert|30|m}} thick deposits are heavily eroded well-exposed outcrops occur south of the volcano at Las Papas. They consist of [[pumice]] fragments of varying sizes embedded within ash,{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=9}} as well as country rock that was torn up and embedded in the flows.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=22}} In the south, pyroclastic flows descending valleys partially overflowed their margins to flood adjacent valleys{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Bustos|Chiodi|Reckziegel|2020|pp=14-15}} and reached the {{Interlanguage link|Bols\u00f3n de Fiambal\u00e1|lt=|es||WD=}}.{{sfn|Seggiaro|Hongn|Castillo|Pereyra|2006|p=29}} North-westward and north-eastward flowing ignimbrites generated ignimbrite fans in the Purulla and Carachipampa valleys, respectively.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Bustos|Chiodi|Reckziegel|2020|pp=9-10}} \n\nThe deposits from this event are also known as Cerro Blanco Ignimbrite, as Ignimbrite of the second cycle or El M\u00e9dano or Purulla Ignimbrite.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=Sintema Cerro Blanco (SCB)}} Formerly these were dated to be 12,000 and 22,000 years old, respectively, and related to the Cerro Blanco and (potentially) Robledo calderas.{{sfn|Brunori|Bignami|Stramondo|Bustos|2013|p=281}} Cerro Blanco is considered to be the youngest caldera of the Central Andes.{{sfn|Brunori|Bignami|Stramondo|Bustos|2013|p=279}}\n\nWith a volume of {{convert|110|km3}} of tephra<ref name=\"Newhall2018\" /> the 4.2 ka eruption has been tentatively{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Bustos|Chiodi|Reckziegel|2020|p=16}} classified as 7 in the [[volcanic explosivity index]],{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=25}} making it comparable to the largest [[Holocene]] volcanic eruptions.<!-- List? -->{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=26}} It is the largest [[Holocene]] eruption in the Central Andes<ref name=\"GVP\" /> and of the Central Volcanic Zone,<ref name=\"GertisserSelf2015\" /> larger than the 1600 [[Huaynaputina]] eruption, the largest historical eruption of the Central Volcanic Zone.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=26}} Most of the erupted volume was ejected by the eruption column, while only about {{convert|8.5|km3}} ended up in pyroclastic flows.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Bustos|Chiodi|Reckziegel|2020|p=4}} Caldera collapse occurred during the course of the eruption, generating the unusually small (for the size of the eruption) Cerro Blanco caldera{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Bustos|Chiodi|Reckziegel|2020|p=15}} through a probably irregular collapse.{{sfn|Di Filippo|Di Nezza|Colombi|Viramonte|2008|p=203}}\n\nSome authors have postulated that mid-Holocene eruptions of Cerro Blanco impacted human communities in the region.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=INTRODUCCI\u00d3N}} Tephra deposits in the [[Formative Period]] [[archaeological site]] of Palo Blanco in the Bols\u00f3n de Fimabal\u00e1 have been attributed to Cerro Blanco,{{sfn|Montero L\u00f3pez|Hongn|Seggiaro|Marrett|2009|p=138}} as is a tephra layer in an archeeological site close to Antofagasta de la Sierra.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=23}} The eruptions of Cerro Blanco may - together with more local [[seismic]] activity -  be responsible for the low population density of the Fiambal\u00e1 region, Chaschuil valley and western [[Tinogasta Department]] during the [[Archaic stage|Archaic period]] between 10,000 and 3,000 years ago.{{sfn|Ratto|Montero|Hongn|2013|p=58-60}} The [[4.2 kiloyear event]] occurred at the same time; it may be in some way related to the Cerro Blanco eruption.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|2019|p=44}}\n\n=== Post-4.2 ka activity ===\n\nAfter the caldera-forming eruption, renewed [[effusive eruption]]s generated the lava domes southwest of and on the margin of the Cerro Blanco caldera{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=14}} and [[phreatic]]/[[phreatomagmatic]] activity occurred.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Chiodi|Bustos|Arnosio|2016|p=225}} The current topography of Cerro Blanco is formed by the deposits from this stage,{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=Sintema Cerro Blanco (SCB)}} whose activity was influenced by intersecting [[fault (geology)|fault]] systems.{{sfn|Brunori|Bignami|Stramondo|Bustos|2013|p=281}}\n\nIt is not clear how long after the 4.2 ka eruption this activity occurred, but it has been grouped as the \"CB{{sub|3}}\" unit (the domes are classified as \"CB{{sub|3}}1\"). This activity also generated block-and-ash deposits (unit \"CB{{sub|3}}2\") on the caldera floor.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=25}} The domes are of [[rhyolitic]] composition, the block-and-ash deposits consist of ash and lapilli{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=14}} and appear to have formed when domes collapsed.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=22}} As lava domes grow, they tend to become unstable as their vertical extent increases until they collapse. Additionally, internally generated explosions appear to have occurred at Cerro Blanco as lava domes grew and sometimes completely destroyed the domes.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Chiodi|Bustos|Arnosio|2016|p=234}}\n\n== Present-day status ==\n\nNo{{efn|{{Interlanguage link|Ferdinand von Wolff|lt=|de||WD=}} linked an 1883 flood in the Bols\u00f3n de Fiambal\u00e1 to an explosion at a volcano he named \"Cerro Blanco\".<ref name=\"VonWolff1929\" />}} eruptions have been observed or recorded at Cerro Blanco,{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=INTRODUCCI\u00d3N}} but various indicators imply that it is still active.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=Implicaciones para la peligrosidad del CVCB}} In 2007-2009 [[seismic swarm]]s were recorded at less than {{convert|15|km}} depth.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=INTRODUCCI\u00d3N}} \n\n[[Geothermal]] activity occurs at Cerro Blanco, and manifests itself on the caldera floor through [[fumarole]]s, hot ground{{sfn|Chiodi|Tassi|B\u00e1ez|Filipovich|2019|p=3}} and reportedly [[hot spring]]s{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=25}}  and [[mud volcano]]es.{{sfn|Brunori|Bignami|Stramondo|Bustos|2013|p=285}} Fumaroles reach temperatures of {{convert|93.7|C}} while temperatures of {{convert|92|C}} have been reported for the hot ground. Past intense [[hydrothermal]] activity appears to have emplaced silicic material up to {{convert|40|cm}} thick,{{sfn|Chiodi|Tassi|B\u00e1ez|Filipovich|2019|p=3}} and [[steam explosions]] took place within the caldera.{{sfn|Conde Serra|2016|p=4}} Active fumaroles and [[clay]] cones formed by fumarolic activity are also found in the phreatic crater.{{sfn|Conde Serra|2016|p=5}} The geothermal system appears to consist of an [[aquifer]] heated by a [[magma chamber]] from below, and has been prospected for possible [[geothermal power]] generation.{{sfn|Conde Serra|2016|p=2}}{{sfn|Chiodi|Tassi|B\u00e1ez|Filipovich|2019|p=13}} \n\nA second geothermal field related to Cerro Blanco is located south of the volcano and is known as Los Hornitos.{{sfn|Chiodi|Tassi|B\u00e1ez|Filipovich|2019|p=2}} It is located in a [[ravine]] and consists of three clusters of bubbling pools, hot springs, up to {{convert|2|m}} high [[travertine]] domes that discharge water and extinct [[geyser]] cones. Water temperatures range between {{convert|32|-|67.4|C}}.{{sfn|Chiodi|Tassi|B\u00e1ez|Filipovich|2019|p=3}} South-westward trending [[fault (geology)|fault]] systems might connect it to the Cerro Blanco magmatic system.{{sfn|Chiodi|Tassi|B\u00e1ez|Filipovich|2019|p=12}} \n\n=== Deformation and hazards ===\n\n[[Subsidence]] at a rate of {{convert|1|-|3|cm/year|in/year}} of the caldera has been noted since 1992{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=25}} in [[InSAR]] images. The rate of subsidence was originally believed to have decreased from over {{convert|2.5|cm/year|in/year}} between 1992-1997 to less than {{convert|1.8|cm/year|in/year}} between 1996-2000{{sfn|Pritchard|Simons|2004|p=26}} and ceased after 2000.{{sfn|Kay|Coira|Mpodozis|2008|p=154}} Later measurements found that the subsidence rate instead had been steady between 1992-2011 with {{convert|1|cm/year|in/year}}, but with a faster phase between 1992-1997,<ref name=\"HendersonPritchard2013\" /> and the locatio the subsidence is centred on has changed over time.{{sfn|Brunori|Bignami|Stramondo|Bustos|2013|p=283}} The subsidence occurs at {{convert|9|-|14|km}} depth{{sfn|Pritchard|Simons|2004|p=34}} and has been related to either a cooling magmatic system, changes in the hydrothermal system{{sfn|Brunori|Bignami|Stramondo|Bustos|2013|p=281}} or to subsidence that followed the 4.2 ka eruption and is still ongoing.<ref name=\"SCN24\" /> Uplift in the area surrounding the caldera has also been identified,{{sfn|Brunori|Bignami|Stramondo|Bustos|2013|p=286}}  \n\nThe [[Servicio Geol\u00f3gico Minero|Argentinian Mining and Geological Service]] has ranked Cerro Blanco eight in its scale of hazardous volcanoes in Argentina.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Bustos|Chiodi|Reckziegel|2020|p=2}} [[Rhyolitic]] caldera systems like Cerro Blanco can produce large eruptions separated by short time intervals. Future activity might involve either a \"boiling-over\" of pyroclastic flows or [[Plinian eruption]]s. Given that the region is sparsely inhabited, the primary effects of a new eruption at Cerro Blanco would come from the eruption column, which could spread tephra eastwards and impact [[air traffic]] there. Also, pyroclastic flows could through narrow valleys reach the Bols\u00f3n de Fiambal\u00e1 valley {{convert|50|km}} south of Cerro Blanco, where many people live.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Arnosio|Chiodi|Ortiz-Ya\u00f1es|2015|loc=Implicaciones para la peligrosidad del CVCB}}\n\n== Research history ==\n\nResearch in the region commenced in the 19th century and was mainly concentrated on [[mining]].{{sfn|Montero L\u00f3pez|Hongn|Affonso Brod|Seggiaro|2010|loc=INTRODUCCI\u00d3N}} Cerro Blanco received attention from scientists after satellite images in the early 20th century observed deflation of the caldera.{{sfn|Kay|Coira|Mpodozis|2006|p=499}} A number of [[Holocene]] tephra layers have been identified in the region, but linking these to specific eruptions has been difficult{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=2}} until 2008-2010 when some of these were linked to the Cerro Blanco vent.{{sfn|Fernandez-Turiel|Perez\u2013Torrado|Rodriguez-Gonzalez|Saavedra|2019|p=4}} Scientific interest has risen in the 2010s due to the discovery of the large 4.2 ka eruption.{{sfn|B\u00e1ez|Bustos|Chiodi|Reckziegel|2020|p=2}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Volcanoes}}\n\n== Notes ==\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"SCN24\">{{Cite book|url=http://www.lillo.org.ar/publicaciones/serie-conservacion-de-la-naturaleza/v24|series=SCN 24|year=2018|p=48|title=La puna argentina. Naturaleza y cultura|publisher=Fundaci\u00f3n Miguel Lillo}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"GertisserSelf2015\">{{Cite journal|last=Gertisser|first=R.|last2=Self|first2=S.|date=July 2015|title=The great 1815 eruption of Tambora and future risks from large-scale volcanism|url=http://doi.wiley.com/10.1111/gto.12099|journal=Geology Today|language=en|volume=31|issue=4|pages=133|doi=10.1111/gto.12099|via=}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Newhall2018\">{{Cite journal|last=Newhall|first=Chris|last2=Self|first2=Stephen|last3=Robock|first3=Alan|date=1 April 2018|title=Anticipating future Volcanic Explosivity Index (VEI) 7 eruptions and their chilling impacts|url=https://pubs.geoscienceworld.org/geosphere/article/14/2/572/529016/Anticipating-future-Volcanic-Explosivity-Index-VEI|journal=Geosphere|language=en|volume=14|issue=2|page=573|doi=10.1130/GES01513.1|via=}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Guzm\u00e1n2017\">{{Cite journal|last=Guzm\u00e1n|first=Silvina|last2=Strecker|first2=Manfred R.|last3=Mart\u00ed|first3=Joan|last4=Petrinovic|first4=Ivan A.|last5=Schildgen|first5=Taylor F.|last6=Grosse|first6=Pablo|last7=Montero-L\u00f3pez|first7=Carolina|last8=Neri|first8=Marco|last9=Carniel|first9=Roberto|last10=Hongn|first10=Fernando D.|last11=Muruaga|first11=Claudia|date=1 May 2017|title=Construction and degradation of a broad volcanic massif: The Vicu\u