{"title_page": "Angela Crawley", "text_new": "{{short description|Scottish politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name             = Angela Crawley\n|honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n|image            = Official portrait of Angela Crawley MP crop 2.jpg\n|office           = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Lanark and Hamilton East (UK Parliament constituency)|Lanark and Hamilton East]]\n|term_start       = 7 May 2015\n|term_end         = \n|predecessor      = [[Jimmy Hood]]\n|successor        =\n|majority         = 5,187 (9.8%)\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1987|6|3|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Hamilton, South Lanarkshire|Hamilton]], [[Scotland]]\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Scottish National Party]]\n|alma_mater       = [[University of Stirling]]<br />[[University of Glasgow]]\n|website          = {{url|angelacrawley.scot|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Angela Crawley''' (born 3 June 1987) is a [[Scottish National Party]] politician. She was first elected as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Lanark and Hamilton East (UK Parliament constituency)|Lanark and Hamilton East]] at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]]. Crawley is the SNP spokesperson for Women and Equalities and a member of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] [[Women and Equalities Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/women-and-equalities-committee/membership/ |title=Women and Equalities Committee - members |publisher=House of Commons |date=8 July 2015 |accessdate=18 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/S14000042#election2015-logo |title= Election 2015: Lanark & Hamilton East parliamentary constituency|work=[[BBC News]]|date= 7 May 2015 |accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Thomson|first=Ross|url= http://www.carlukegazette.co.uk/news/local-headlines/angela-crawley-wins-lanark-seat-from-jim-hood-1-3766951 |title=Angela Crawley wins Lanark seat from Jim Hood|work=Carluke Gazette|date=8 May 2015 |accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nBorn in [[Hamilton, South Lanarkshire|Hamilton]], Crawley attended [[John Ogilvie High School]]. She studied Politics at the [[University of Stirling]], graduating with a BA degree. She then spent several years living and working in [[Brighton]] for the Educational Travel Group.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BVWqCQAAQBAJ&pg=PT216&lpg=PT216&dq=angela+crawley+Educational+Travel+Group#v=onepage&q=angela%20crawley%20Educational%20Travel%20Group&f=false|title=The Politicos Guide to the New House of Commons 2015: Profiles of the New MPs and Analysis of the 2015 General Election Results|last=Carr|first=Tim|date=2015-05-18|publisher=Biteback Publishing|isbn=9781849549240|language=en}}</ref> After being elected to Parliament,  she received an LLB degree in Law from the [[University of Glasgow]].\n\nShe first stood for election to [[South Lanarkshire Council]] for the Hamilton South ward and was elected at the [[2012 South Lanarkshire Council election|2012 local elections]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.stv.tv/west-central/98255-tears-of-shock-and-delight-at-south-lanarkshires-local-elections/ |title=Tears of shock and delight at South Lanarkshire's local elections |first=Gillian |last=Provan |work=[[STV News]]|date=4 May 2012 |accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref> with 1,255 first preferences and taking the second seat in the ward, exceeding the quota.\n\nIn 2014, she was appointed as the National Convenor of the SNP's youth wing, [[Young Scots for Independence]]; also sitting on the party's National Executive Committee. She is the SNP Spokesperson for Young People and Community Resources.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/angela-crawley|title=Angela Crawley|website=politics.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-03-27}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Crawley was named in the ''[[Forbes]]'' 30 Under 30 list for her work in Parliament.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/30-under-30-europe-2017/law-policy/|title=30 Under 30 Europe 2017: Law & Policy|website=Forbes|access-date=2018-03-27}}</ref> She very narrowly retained her Hamilton East and Lanark seat at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 snap general election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/S14000042|title=Lanark & Hamilton East parliamentary constituency - Election 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-03-27|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nCrawley has called for victims of domestic abuse to be exempted from the child maintenance charge, and wrote a letter to Home Secretary [[Amber Rudd]] on the issue in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.holyrood.com/articles/news/snp-mp-angela-crawley-calls-end-%E2%80%98cruel-and-callous%E2%80%99-child-maintenance-charges-domestic|title=SNP MP Angela Crawley calls for end to 'cruel and callous' child maintenance charges for domestic abuse victims|date=2017-02-10|work=Holyrood Magazine|access-date=2018-03-27|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thenational.scot/news/15905320.May_pushed_to_scrap____cruel____child_maintenance_fees/|title=May pushed to scrap 'cruel' child maintenance fees|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2018-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.commonspace.scot/articles/10301/angela-crawley-mp-time-axe-tax-survivors-domestic-abuse|title=Angela Crawley MP: \"Time to axe the tax for survivors of domestic abuse\"|work=CommonSpace|access-date=2018-03-27|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.carlukegazette.co.uk/news/mp-calls-for-an-end-to-shameful-tax-1-4709653|title=MP calls for an end to 'shameful tax'|access-date=2018-03-27|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn February 2016, she was included in ''[[The Independent]]'''s group photograph of 28 LGBT MPs and peers.<ref>{{cite news|last=Leftly|first=Mark|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/gay-mps-the-photograph-that-shows-westminsters-attitude-towards-lgbt-politicians-is-changing-a6886771.html|title=Gay MPs: The photograph that shows Westminster's attitude towards LGBT politicians is changing|work=The Independent|date=20 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://www.snp.org/angela_crawley profile] on SNP website\n{{UK MP links\n| parliament   = angela-crawley/4469\n| hansard      = \n| hansardcurr  =\n| guardian     =\n| publicwhip   = Angela_Crawley&mpc=Lanark_and_Hamilton_East&house=commons\n| theywork     = 25295/angela_crawley/lanark_and_hamilton_east\n| record       =\n| bbc          = 122103.stm\n| journalisted =\n}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jimmy Hood]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Lanark and Hamilton East (UK Parliament constituency)|Lanark and Hamilton East]]|years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{SNP MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crawley, Angela}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at John Ogilvie High School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Stirling]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Scottish constituencies]]\n[[Category:Lesbian politicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from Scotland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Scottish constituencies]]\n[[Category:People from Hamilton, South Lanarkshire]]\n[[Category:Scottish National Party councillors]]\n[[Category:Scottish National Party MPs]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Scottish politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name             = Angela Crawley\n|honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n|image            = Official portrait of Angela Crawley MP crop 2.jpg\n|office           = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Lanark and Hamilton East (UK Parliament constituency)|Lanark and Hamilton East]]\n|term_start       = 7 May 2015\n|term_end         = \n|predecessor      = [[Jimmy Hood]]\n|successor        =\n|majority         = 5,187 (9.8%)\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1987|6|3|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Hamilton, South Lanarkshire|Hamilton]], [[Scotland]]\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Scottish National Party]]\n|alma_mater       = [[University of Stirling]]<br />[[University of Glasgow]]\n|website          = {{url|angelacrawley.scot|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Angela Crawley''' (born 3 June 1987) is a [[Scottish National Party]] politician. She was first elected as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Lanark and Hamilton East (UK Parliament constituency)|Lanark and Hamilton East]] at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]]. Crawley is the SNP spokesperson for Women and Equalities and a member of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] [[Women and Equalities Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/women-and-equalities-committee/membership/ |title=Women and Equalities Committee - members |publisher=House of Commons |date=8 July 2015 |accessdate=18 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/S14000042#election2015-logo |title= Election 2015: Lanark & Hamilton East parliamentary constituency|work=[[BBC News]]|date= 7 May 2015 |accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Thomson|first=Ross|url= http://www.carlukegazette.co.uk/news/local-headlines/angela-crawley-wins-lanark-seat-from-jim-hood-1-3766951 |title=Angela Crawley wins Lanark seat from Jim Hood|work=Carluke Gazette|date=8 May 2015 |accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nBorn in [[Hamilton, South Lanarkshire|Hamilton]], Crawley attended [[John Ogilvie High School]]. She studied Politics at the [[University of Stirling]], graduating with a BA degree. She then spent several years living and working in [[Brighton]] for the Educational Travel Group.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BVWqCQAAQBAJ&pg=PT216&lpg=PT216&dq=angela+crawley+Educational+Travel+Group#v=onepage&q=angela%20crawley%20Educational%20Travel%20Group&f=false|title=The Politicos Guide to the New House of Commons 2015: Profiles of the New MPs and Analysis of the 2015 General Election Results|last=Carr|first=Tim|date=2015-05-18|publisher=Biteback Publishing|isbn=9781849549240|language=en}}</ref> After being elected to Parliament,  she received an LLB degree in Law from the [[University of Glasgow]].\n\nShe first stood for election to [[South Lanarkshire Council]] for the Hamilton South ward and was elected at the [[2012 South Lanarkshire Council election|2012 local elections]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.stv.tv/west-central/98255-tears-of-shock-and-delight-at-south-lanarkshires-local-elections/ |title=Tears of shock and delight at South Lanarkshire's local elections |first=Gillian |last=Provan |work=[[STV News]]|date=4 May 2012 |accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref> with 1,255 first preferences and taking the second seat in the ward, exceeding the quota.\n\nIn 2014, she was appointed as the National Convenor of the SNP\u2019s youth wing, [[Young Scots for Independence]]; also sitting on the party\u2019s National Executive Committee. She is the SNP Spokesperson for Young People and Community Resources.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/angela-crawley|title=Angela Crawley|website=politics.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-03-27}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Crawley was named in the ''[[Forbes]]'' 30 Under 30 list for her work in Parliament.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/30-under-30-europe-2017/law-policy/|title=30 Under 30 Europe 2017: Law & Policy|website=Forbes|access-date=2018-03-27}}</ref> She very narrowly retained her Hamilton East and Lanark seat at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 snap general election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/S14000042|title=Lanark & Hamilton East parliamentary constituency - Election 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-03-27|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nCrawley has called for victims of domestic abuse to be exempted from the child maintenance charge, and wrote a letter to Home Secretary [[Amber Rudd]] on the issue in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.holyrood.com/articles/news/snp-mp-angela-crawley-calls-end-%E2%80%98cruel-and-callous%E2%80%99-child-maintenance-charges-domestic|title=SNP MP Angela Crawley calls for end to 'cruel and callous' child maintenance charges for domestic abuse victims|date=2017-02-10|work=Holyrood Magazine|access-date=2018-03-27|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thenational.scot/news/15905320.May_pushed_to_scrap____cruel____child_maintenance_fees/|title=May pushed to scrap 'cruel' child maintenance fees|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2018-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.commonspace.scot/articles/10301/angela-crawley-mp-time-axe-tax-survivors-domestic-abuse|title=Angela Crawley MP: \"Time to axe the tax for survivors of domestic abuse\"|work=CommonSpace|access-date=2018-03-27|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.carlukegazette.co.uk/news/mp-calls-for-an-end-to-shameful-tax-1-4709653|title=MP calls for an end to 'shameful tax'|access-date=2018-03-27|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn February 2016, she was included in ''[[The Independent]]'''s group photograph of 28 LGBT MPs and peers.<ref>{{cite news|last=Leftly|first=Mark|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/gay-mps-the-photograph-that-shows-westminsters-attitude-towards-lgbt-politicians-is-changing-a6886771.html|title=Gay MPs: The photograph that shows Westminster's attitude towards LGBT politicians is changing|work=The Independent|date=20 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://www.snp.org/angela_crawley profile] on SNP website\n{{UK MP links\n| parliament   = angela-crawley/4469\n| hansard      = \n| hansardcurr  =\n| guardian     =\n| publicwhip   = Angela_Crawley&mpc=Lanark_and_Hamilton_East&house=commons\n| theywork     = 25295/angela_crawley/lanark_and_hamilton_east\n| record       =\n| bbc          = 122103.stm\n| journalisted =\n}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jimmy Hood]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Lanark and Hamilton East (UK Parliament constituency)|Lanark and Hamilton East]]|years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{SNP MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crawley, Angela}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at John Ogilvie High School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Stirling]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Scottish constituencies]]\n[[Category:Lesbian politicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from Scotland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Scottish constituencies]]\n[[Category:People from Hamilton, South Lanarkshire]]\n[[Category:Scottish National Party councillors]]\n[[Category:Scottish National Party MPs]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angela_Crawley"}
{"title_page": "Karkarthar", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2019}}\n{{more footnotes|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox Ethnic group\n|group     = Karkathar\n|image = \n|popplace  = [[Tamil Nadu]]\n|languages = [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n|religions = [[Hinduism]]\n|related   = [[Vellalar]], [[Tamil people]]\n}}\n\n'''Karkathar''' is a [[Hindus|Hindu]] [[caste]] in the [[Indian people|Indian]] [[States and union territories of India|state]] of [[Tamil Nadu]]. It is a sub-caste of the greater [[Vellalar]] community of [[India]]. They are also known as Karalar.\n\n==Etymology==\n\nKarkathar (Kar-cloud, Kathar- protector)  means protector of clouds in [[Tamil language|Tamil]] .{{sfnp|Rajannan|1992|p=157|ps=}}\nAs per cultural history, a sector of people who use to control rain through traditional technologies and thus harvest in the Chola regime is responsible to ensure the Food Safety and farming in the kingdom is referred to as KarKathar. They belong to a sub-caste of Vellalar. They also remind as trustworthy think tanks for empowers and kings performed the roles of ministers and intelligence - National security, especially in then kaveripoompatinam ( today's poombukar, in Tamilnadu, India) \nEven today, then Chola dynasty town and villages have streets named Madavalaagam and Mahadhanam are either close to temple or fort and works closely with Government to ensure food safety. Their descendants still reside in some of those areas for centuries-old houses\n\n==History==\n\nAccording to tradition, the Karkathar migrated from the Gangetic plains and over time spread over the entire macro region of present day [[Tamil Nadu]]. According to ''satakams'', the [[Pandya]] country was settled by these people after they had resided in the [[Chola]] country. According to historian [[Burton Stein]], this theory is purely mythical.{{sfnp|Stein|1980|p=320|ps=}}\n\nAccording to anthropologist [[Nicholas Dirks|Nicholas B. Dirks]], the [[Pudukottai]] region was sparsely populated until the early Chola period. But with the beginning of the [[Chola]] era, there is strong evidence of increasing agrarian settlement, the growth of villages, institutions, the construction and expansion of temples.{{sfnp|Dirks|1993|p=139|ps=}} According to the Tekkattur manuscript, the Karkathar were initially divided into ''Kan\u0101ttars'' and ''K\u014dn\u0101ttars'', each of which had many exogamous sub-divisions. K\u014dn\u0101du or the land of the king ([[Chola]] country) mostly consisted of the regions north of the river Vellar except for the western part of the state where it included certain regions south of the river as well. Kan\u0101du, literally meaning the land of the forests was included in the [[Pandya]] country. The manuscript goes on to describe the decline in the position of the Karkathar after the initial golden age due to the fighting between the two branches over various issues such as land, rights to the water of the river Vellar, temples etc. and the subsequent settlement and dominance of the Maravars in the region who were initially imported from [[Ramnad]] by both branches. The copper plate inscriptions held by every Maravar community in the region indicates that the K\u014dn\u0101ttu vellalar were victorious in the end.{{sfnp|Dirks|1993|p=140|ps=}}\n\nAccording to historian Arokiaswami, the [[Irunk\u014dv\u0113l|Irukkuvels]] of Kodumbalur who were the main allies of the Cholas from an early period were all Vellalars. According to Dirks, the local sources like palm leaf manuscripts, copper plate inscriptions and many of the origin stories also indicate that there was a relationship between the Irukkuvel family of chieftains and the Karkathar vellalar community and he says, that the Irukkuvel titles such as ''V\u0113l\u0101r'' as in ''Madurantaka Irukkuv\u0113l\u0101r'', ''\u015aembiyan Irukkuv\u0113l\u0101r'', etc. proves that the Irukkuvels were indeed Vellalar.{{sfnp|Dirks|1993|p=149|ps=}}<ref name=\"Volume 6 of A Topographical List of Inscriptions in the Tamil Nadu and Kerala States, page 47, 49\">''Volume 6 of A Topographical List of Inscriptions in the Tamil Nadu and Kerala States, page 47, 49''</ref> Stein disputes Arokiaswami's claim that the Irukkuvels were Vellalar.{{sfnp|Dirks|1993|p=149|ps=}}\n\n==Distribution==\nAreas of Karkarthar population have included:\n\n* [[Tanjore]]. [[Kumbakonam]], [[Thirupanandal]], [[Nagapattinam]] , [[Thiruvarur]] , [[Mayavaram]], [[Trichy]], [[Chidambaram]] ((Pudukottai)), [[Cuddalore]], Sripuram districts.{{sfnp|Mathur|1994|p=153|ps=}}\n\n* [[Attur]] and [[Omalur]] taluks.{{sfnp|Baliga|1967|p=121|ps=}}\n\n==References==\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{citation |title=Salem cyclopedia: a cultural and historical dictionary of Salem District, Tamil Nadu |first=Busnagi |last=Rajannan |publisher=Institute of Kongu Studies |year=1992 |url=https://books.google.com/books&id=Ez9uAAAAMAAJ}}\n* {{citation |title=Madras District Gazetteers: Salem, Madras |first=B. S. |last=Baliga |publisher=Superintendent, Government Press |year=1967 |url=https://books.google.com/books&id=FWZDAAAAYAAJ}}\n* {{citation |title=The hollow crown: ethnohistory of an Indian kingdom |first=Nicholas B. |last=Dirks |authorlink=Nicholas Dirks |edition=Reprinted |year=1993 |publisher=University of Michigan Press |isbn=9780472081875 |url=https://books.google.com/books&id=cegr6zH9PFEC}}\n* {{citation |title=Peasant state and society in medieval South India |first=Burton |last=Stein |authorlink=Burton Stein |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1980 |url=https://books.google.com/books&id=b-9HAAAAMAAJ}}\n* {{citation |title=Volume 10 of Karnataka State Gazetteer, Karnataka (India)}}\n* {{citation |title=Applied anthropology and challenges of development in India |first=P. R. G. |last=Mathur |publisher=Punthi-Pustak |year=1994 |isbn=9788185094793 |url=https://books.google.com/books&id=PuuAAAAAMAAJ}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |title=People of India: A - G. |volume=4}}\n* {{cite book |title=Social science and social concern: felicitation volume in honour of Professor B.K. Roy Burman}}\n* {{cite book |title=Tamil culture in Ceylon: a general introduction |first=M. D. |last=Raghavan}}\n\n[[Category:Vellalar]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Tamil Nadu]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2019}}\n{{more footnotes|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox Ethnic group\n|group     = Karkathar\n|image = \n|popplace  = [[Tamil Nadu]]\n|languages = [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n|religions = [[Hinduism]]\n|related   = [[Vellalar]], [[Tamil people]]\n}}\n\n'''Karkathar''' is a [[Hindus|Hindu]] [[caste]] in the [[Indian people|Indian]] [[States and union territories of India|state]] of [[Tamil Nadu]]. It is a sub-caste of the greater [[Vellalar]] community of [[India]]. They are also known as Karalar.\n\n==Etymology==\n\nKarkathar (Kar-cloud, Kathar- protector)  means protector of clouds in [[Tamil language|Tamil]] .{{sfnp|Rajannan|1992|p=157|ps=}}\n\n==History==\n\nAccording to tradition, the Karkathar migrated from the Gangetic plains and over time spread over the entire macro region of present day [[Tamil Nadu]]. According to ''satakams'', the [[Pandya]] country was settled by these people after they had resided in the [[Chola]] country. According to historian [[Burton Stein]], this theory is purely mythical.{{sfnp|Stein|1980|p=320|ps=}}\n\nAccording to anthropologist [[Nicholas Dirks|Nicholas B. Dirks]], the [[Pudukottai]] region was sparsely populated until the early Chola period. But with the beginning of the [[Chola]] era, there is strong evidence of increasing agrarian settlement, the growth of villages, institutions, the construction and expansion of temples.{{sfnp|Dirks|1993|p=139|ps=}} According to the Tekkattur manuscript, the Karkathar were initially divided into ''Kan\u0101ttars'' and ''K\u014dn\u0101ttars'', each of which had many exogamous sub-divisions. K\u014dn\u0101du or the land of the king ([[Chola]] country) mostly consisted of the regions north of the river Vellar except for the western part of the state where it included certain regions south of the river as well. Kan\u0101du, literally meaning the land of the forests was included in the [[Pandya]] country. The manuscript goes on to describe the decline in the position of the Karkathar after the initial golden age due to the fighting between the two branches over various issues such as land, rights to the water of the river Vellar, temples etc. and the subsequent settlement and dominance of the Maravars in the region who were initially imported from [[Ramnad]] by both branches. The copper plate inscriptions held by every Maravar community in the region indicates that the K\u014dn\u0101ttu vellalar were victorious in the end.{{sfnp|Dirks|1993|p=140|ps=}}\n\nAccording to historian Arokiaswami, the [[Irunk\u014dv\u0113l|Irukkuvels]] of Kodumbalur who were the main allies of the Cholas from an early period were all Vellalars. According to Dirks, the local sources like palm leaf manuscripts, copper plate inscriptions and many of the origin stories also indicate that there was a relationship between the Irukkuvel family of chieftains and the Karkathar vellalar community and he says, that the Irukkuvel titles such as ''V\u0113l\u0101r'' as in ''Madurantaka Irukkuv\u0113l\u0101r'', ''\u015aembiyan Irukkuv\u0113l\u0101r'', etc. proves that the Irukkuvels were indeed Vellalar.{{sfnp|Dirks|1993|p=149|ps=}}<ref name=\"Volume 6 of A Topographical List of Inscriptions in the Tamil Nadu and Kerala States, page 47, 49\">''Volume 6 of A Topographical List of Inscriptions in the Tamil Nadu and Kerala States, page 47, 49''</ref> Stein disputes Arokiaswami's claim that the Irukkuvels were Vellalar.{{sfnp|Dirks|1993|p=149|ps=}}\n\n==Distribution==\nAreas of Karkarthar population have included:\n\n* [[Tanjore]]. [[Kumbakonam]], [[Thirupanandal]], [[Nagapattinam]] , [[Thiruvarur]] , [[Mayavaram]], [[Trichy]], [[Chidambaram]] ((Pudukottai)), [[Cuddalore]], Sripuram districts.{{sfnp|Mathur|1994|p=153|ps=}}\n\n* [[Attur]] and [[Omalur]] taluks.{{sfnp|Baliga|1967|p=121|ps=}}\n\n==References==\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{citation |title=Salem cyclopedia: a cultural and historical dictionary of Salem District, Tamil Nadu |first=Busnagi |last=Rajannan |publisher=Institute of Kongu Studies |year=1992 |url=https://books.google.com/books&id=Ez9uAAAAMAAJ}}\n* {{citation |title=Madras District Gazetteers: Salem, Madras |first=B. S. |last=Baliga |publisher=Superintendent, Government Press |year=1967 |url=https://books.google.com/books&id=FWZDAAAAYAAJ}}\n* {{citation |title=The hollow crown: ethnohistory of an Indian kingdom |first=Nicholas B. |last=Dirks |authorlink=Nicholas Dirks |edition=Reprinted |year=1993 |publisher=University of Michigan Press |isbn=9780472081875 |url=https://books.google.com/books&id=cegr6zH9PFEC}}\n* {{citation |title=Peasant state and society in medieval South India |first=Burton |last=Stein |authorlink=Burton Stein |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1980 |url=https://books.google.com/books&id=b-9HAAAAMAAJ}}\n* {{citation |title=Volume 10 of Karnataka State Gazetteer, Karnataka (India)}}\n* {{citation |title=Applied anthropology and challenges of development in India |first=P. R. G. |last=Mathur |publisher=Punthi-Pustak |year=1994 |isbn=9788185094793 |url=https://books.google.com/books&id=PuuAAAAAMAAJ}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |title=People of India: A - G. |volume=4}}\n* {{cite book |title=Social science and social concern: felicitation volume in honour of Professor B.K. Roy Burman}}\n* {{cite book |title=Tamil culture in Ceylon: a general introduction |first=M. D. |last=Raghavan}}\n\n[[Category:Vellalar]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Tamil Nadu]]\n", "name_user": "Ashokb23", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u20