{"title_page": "Robert Courts", "text_new": "{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Robert Courts\n| image = Official portrait of Robert Courts MP crop 2.jpg\n| office1 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Witney (UK Parliament constituency)|Witney]]\n| honorific-prefix = \n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| predecessor1 = [[David Cameron]]\n| majority1 = 15,177 (24.7%)\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1978|10|21}}<ref>{{cite web|title=MyParliament - Biography for Robert Courts|url=http://myparliament.info/Member/4589|website=My Parliament}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Stockport]], [[Greater Manchester]], England<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/results/united-kingdom-records-in-birth-marriage-death-and-parish-records/and_births-and-baptisms?firstname=robert&firstname_variants=true&lastname=courts&yearofbirth=1978&yearofbirth_offset=5|title=Search Results - Birth, Marriage, Death - findmypast.co.uk|website=search.findmypast.co.uk}}</ref>\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Sheffield]]\n| website = {{url|robertcourts.co.uk|Official website}}\n| term_start1 = 20 October 2016\n| term_end1 =\n| successor1 =\n}}\n'''Robert Alexander Courts''' (born 21 October 1978) is a British [[barrister]] and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician who has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for Witney since winning the seat at [[2016 Witney by-election|by-election in 2016]].  He retained his seat in the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]] and [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]]s. In August 2019 Courts was appointed [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to the [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nCourts was schooled at [[Berkhamsted School]], where he was head of Fry's House, before reading law at the [[University of Sheffield]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.dehavilland.co.uk/insight-blog-uk/whither-witney-election-everyones-watching|title=Whither Witney? The by-election everyone's watching|website=www1.dehavilland.co.uk|date=23 September 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824013309/https://www1.dehavilland.co.uk/insight-blog-uk/whither-witney-election-everyones-watching|archivedate=24 August 2017}}</ref><ref>https://uk.linkedin.com/in/robertcourts</ref> Courts was called to the Bar at [[Lincoln's Inn]] in 2003 and practises as a [[barrister]] at 3PB Chambers.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.3pb.co.uk/profile/robert-courts|title=Robert Courts \u2013 3 Paper Buildings Barristers' Chambers|website=www.3pb.co.uk|access-date=11 October 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012081000/http://www.3pb.co.uk/profile/robert-courts|archivedate=12 October 2016}}</ref> He worked in [[Wellington, New Zealand]], at the [[Crown Law Office (New Zealand)|Crown Law Office]] (Legal Advisors) for the [[Government of New Zealand|New Zealand Government]] in 2009.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Political career==\nCourts stood as a Council candidate in Solihull in 2002 but was unsuccessful.\nCourts was elected a Conservative member of [[West Oxfordshire District Council]] in 2014.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHe was selected as the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] candidate to replace [[David Cameron]]\u2014who had resigned as [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] in July and from Parliament in September\u2014as Member of Parliament in the [[2016 Witney by-election]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/sep/22/robert-courts-chosen-tory-candidate-david-cameron-constituency|title=Robert Courts chosen as Tory candidate for David Cameron's constituency|last=Association|first=Press|date=22 September 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=11 October 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012083048/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/sep/22/robert-courts-chosen-tory-candidate-david-cameron-constituency|archivedate=12 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nCourts retained the seat for the Conservatives in the 20 October 2016 by-election, but his majority of 5,702 was considerably smaller than the 25,155-strong majority Cameron won in the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]]. He was sworn into the House on 24 October.<ref name=\"bbc.com\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-37750114|title=Tracy Brabin and Robert Courts sworn in as MPs|date=24 October 2016|website=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=25 November 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030080504/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-37750114|archivedate=30 October 2016}}</ref> He increased his majority to over 21,000 in the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|snap 2017 general election]].\n\nCourts supported the successful 'Leave' campaign in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|EU referendum on 23 June 2016]].<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news|last1=Elgot|first1=Jessica|title=Witney byelection: hard Brexit may be key issue in Cameron's former constituency|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/oct/11/witney-byelection-hard-brexit-may-be-key-issue-in-camerons-former-constituency|accessdate=13 October 2016|work=The Guardian|date=11 October 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012192815/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/oct/11/witney-byelection-hard-brexit-may-be-key-issue-in-camerons-former-constituency|archivedate=12 October 2016}}</ref> He is a member of the [[Euroscepticism in the United Kingdom|eurosceptic]] [[European Research Group]], having subscribed in April 2017.<ref name=\"Robert Courts - IPSA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theipsa.org.uk/mp-costs/your-mp/robert-courts/|title=Robert Courts - IPSA|website=IPSA|language=en|access-date=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nCourts was appointed [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] (PPS) for the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] in January 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/list-of-parliamentary-private-secretaries-pps-january-2018 |title=List of Parliamentary Private Secretaries (PPS): January 2018 | website=Gov.uk}}</ref> but resigned as a PPS on 15 July 2018, in protest of the White Paper on Exiting the European Union and the Chequers Agreement.<ref name=\"Sky News\">{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/may-suffers-yet-another-resignation-as-robert-courts-quits-over-her-brexit-plan-11438048 |title=May suffers yet another resignation as Robert Courts quits over her Brexit plan |work=Sky News |date=15 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Mikhailova, Anna\">{{cite news|author=Mikhailova, Anna |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/07/15/theresa-may-faces-eighth-resignation-brexit-plans-nine-days/ |title=Theresa May hit by her eighth resignation over Brexit plans in nine days, as ministerial aide quits |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=15 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Sabbagh, Dan\">{{cite news|author=Sabbagh, Dan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/15/theresa-may-faces-rebellion-from-brexit-hardliners-in-customs-bill-vote |title=Theresa May faces rebellion from Brexit hardliners in customs bill vote |work=The Guardian |date=15 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nCourts' main Parliamentary interests are defence and foreign policy. He is credited by the House of Commons library with helping to lead the \u201cparliamentary pressure\u201d that led to the announcement of the Ministry of Defence's [[Future of the Royal Air Force#Combat Air Strategy and Team Tempest|Combat Air Strategy]], the programme for the eventual replacement of the [[Eurofighter Typhoon]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brooke-Holland|first=Louisa|date=2018-05-15|title=Prospects for combat air: What follows Typhoon and Lightning?|url=https://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-8304 | website=UK Parliament }}</ref> He has become one of the leading parliamentary speakers on the Armed Forces, with a particular specialisation in the [[Royal Air Force]]. Courts represents [[RAF Brize Norton]], the largest RAF base in the UK, and serves as the Vice Chair (RAF) of the All-Party Parliamentary Group for the Armed Forces.\n\nOn 8 May 2019, Courts initiated and led a parliamentary debate on 'Human Rights in West Papua.'<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2019-05-08/debates/01B3C1C1-872A-470F-811A-6F17091FCFFF/WestPapuaHumanRights|title=West Papua: Human Rights - Hansard|website=hansard.parliament.uk|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref> This historic debate was the first time MPs had ever debated [[Western New Guinea|West Papua]] in the House of Commons.\n\nAs Chair of the All-Party Parliamentary Group for Small and Micro Business, Courts has been a leading parliamentary campaigner for the interests of small businesses. Courts has consistently protested against the increasing bureaucracy and red tape facing small firms, and called for a full review of the business rates system.\n\nCourts is known for his small state, [[Libertarianism|libertarian]] leanings and identifies with the [[Austrian School|Austrian School of Economics]].\n\nRegarding parliamentary procedure, Courts has been an outspoken critic of [[Early day motion|Early Day Motions]] (EDMs), describing them as \"parliamentary graffiti.\" Courts has said that EDMs are generally tabled by MPs on behalf of \"lobbyists or groups keen to show themselves as doing something\", that they are \"politically impotent\" and a waste of taxpayers' money.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.robertcourts.co.uk/early-day-motions|title=Early Day Motions|website=Robert Courts|language=en|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref>\n\nCourts currently serves on two Parliamentary Select Committees: the Transport Committee, which he was elected to in October 2018, and the Justice Committee, which he joined in January 2019.\n\nIn August 2019, Courts was appointed [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to the Secretary of the State for the Environment, [[Theresa Villiers]].\n\nCourts is a council member of the [[Air League]].<ref>https://www.airleague.co.uk/about-us/key-people/</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCourts lives with his wife and two young children in the village of [[Bladon]]. He is a member of St Martin's Church Parochial Church Council.\n\nHe has been a member of the [[International Churchill Society|Churchill Centre]] for many years, and reviews books about [[Winston Churchill|Churchill]] in the quarterly journal, ''Finest Hour''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://winstonchurchill.org/publications/finest-hour/finest-hour-180/books-arts-curiosities-european-unity/|title=Books, Arts, & Curiosities - European Unity - Finest Hour|date=2018-08-08|website=The International Churchill Society|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref>\n\nCourts is an accomplished blues guitarist and enjoys cycling, swimming, and hiking. He is also a diver, interested in the marine environment; he is a member of the [[Marine Conservation Society]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.robertcourts.co.uk/ Robert Courts official website]\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=robert-courts/4589 |publicwhip=Robert_Courts |theywork=robert_courts}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Cameron]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Witney (UK Parliament constituency)|Witney]]|years=[[2016 Witney by-election|2016]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{South East Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Courts, Robert}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of Lincoln's Inn]]\n[[Category:New Zealand lawyers]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:British barristers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Berkhamsted School]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Sheffield]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Oxfordshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Robert Courts\n| image = Official portrait of Robert Courts MP crop 2.jpg\n| office1 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Witney (UK Parliament constituency)|Witney]]\n| honorific-prefix = \n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| predecessor1 = [[David Cameron]]\n| majority1 = 15,177 (24.7%)\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1978|10|21}}<ref>{{cite web|title=MyParliament - Biography for Robert Courts|url=http://myparliament.info/Member/4589|website=My Parliament}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Stockport]], [[Greater Manchester]], England<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/results/united-kingdom-records-in-birth-marriage-death-and-parish-records/and_births-and-baptisms?firstname=robert&firstname_variants=true&lastname=courts&yearofbirth=1978&yearofbirth_offset=5|title=Search Results - Birth, Marriage, Death - findmypast.co.uk|website=search.findmypast.co.uk}}</ref>\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Sheffield]]\n| website = {{url|robertcourts.co.uk|Official website}}\n| term_start1 = 20 October 2016\n| term_end1 =\n| successor1 =\n}}\n'''Robert Alexander Courts''' (born 21 October 1978) is a British [[barrister]] and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician who has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for Witney since winning the seat at [[2016 Witney by-election|by-election in 2016]].  He retained his seat in the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]] and [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]]s. In August 2019 Courts was appointed [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to the [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nCourts was schooled at [[Berkhamsted School]], where he was head of Fry\u2019s House, before reading law at the [[University of Sheffield]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.dehavilland.co.uk/insight-blog-uk/whither-witney-election-everyones-watching|title=Whither Witney? The by-election everyone's watching|website=www1.dehavilland.co.uk|date=23 September 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824013309/https://www1.dehavilland.co.uk/insight-blog-uk/whither-witney-election-everyones-watching|archivedate=24 August 2017}}</ref><ref>https://uk.linkedin.com/in/robertcourts</ref> Courts was called to the Bar at [[Lincoln's Inn]] in 2003 and practises as a [[barrister]] at 3PB Chambers.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.3pb.co.uk/profile/robert-courts|title=Robert Courts \u2013 3 Paper Buildings Barristers' Chambers|website=www.3pb.co.uk|access-date=11 October 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012081000/http://www.3pb.co.uk/profile/robert-courts|archivedate=12 October 2016}}</ref> He worked in [[Wellington, New Zealand]], at the [[Crown Law Office (New Zealand)|Crown Law Office]] (Legal Advisors) for the [[Government of New Zealand|New Zealand Government]] in 2009.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Political career==\nCourts stood as a Council candidate in Solihull in 2002 but was unsuccessful.\nCourts was elected a Conservative member of [[West Oxfordshire District Council]] in 2014.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHe was selected as the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] candidate to replace [[David Cameron]]\u2014who had resigned as [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] in July and from Parliament in September\u2014as Member of Parliament in the [[2016 Witney by-election]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/sep/22/robert-courts-chosen-tory-candidate-david-cameron-constituency|title=Robert Courts chosen as Tory candidate for David Cameron's constituency|last=Association|first=Press|date=22 September 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=11 October 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012083048/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/sep/22/robert-courts-chosen-tory-candidate-david-cameron-constituency|archivedate=12 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nCourts retained the seat for the Conservatives in the 20 October 2016 by-election, but his majority of 5,702 was considerably smaller than the 25,155-strong majority Cameron won in the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]]. He was sworn into the House on 24 October.<ref name=\"bbc.com\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-37750114|title=Tracy Brabin and Robert Courts sworn in as MPs|date=24 October 2016|website=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=25 November 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030080504/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-37750114|archivedate=30 October 2016}}</ref> He increased his majority to over 21,000 in the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|snap 2017 general election]].\n\nCourts supported the successful 'Leave' campaign in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|EU referendum on 23 June 2016]].<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news|last1=Elgot|first1=Jessica|title=Witney byelection: hard Brexit may be key issue in Cameron's former constituency|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/oct/11/witney-byelection-hard-brexit-may-be-key-issue-in-camerons-former-constituency|accessdate=13 October 2016|work=The Guardian|date=11 October 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012192815/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/oct/11/witney-byelection-hard-brexit-may-be-key-issue-in-camerons-former-constituency|archivedate=12 October 2016}}</ref> He is a member of the [[Euroscepticism in the United Kingdom|eurosceptic]] [[European Research Group]], having subscribed in April 2017.<ref name=\"Robert Courts - IPSA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theipsa.org.uk/mp-costs/your-mp/robert-courts/|title=Robert Courts - IPSA|website=IPSA|language=en|access-date=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nCourts was appointed [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] (PPS) for the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] in January 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/list-of-parliamentary-private-secretaries-pps-january-2018 |title=List of Parliamentary Private Secretaries (PPS): January 2018 | website=Gov.uk}}</ref> but resigned as a PPS on 15 July 2018, in protest of the White Paper on Exiting the European Union and the Chequers Agreement.<ref name=\"Sky News\">{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/may-suffers-yet-another-resignation-as-robert-courts-quits-over-her-brexit-plan-11438048 |title=May suffers yet another resignation as Robert Courts quits over her Brexit plan |work=Sky News |date=15 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Mikhailova, Anna\">{{cite news|author=Mikhailova, Anna |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/07/15/theresa-may-faces-eighth-resignation-brexit-plans-nine-days/ |title=Theresa May hit by her eighth resignation over Brexit plans in nine days, as ministerial aide quits |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=15 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Sabbagh, Dan\">{{cite news|author=Sabbagh, Dan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/15/theresa-may-faces-rebellion-from-brexit-hardliners-in-customs-bill-vote |title=Theresa May faces rebellion from Brexit hardliners in customs bill vote |work=The Guardian |date=15 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nCourts' main Parliamentary interests are defence and foreign policy. He is credited by the House of Commons library with helping to lead the \u201cparliamentary pressure\u201d that led to the announcement of the Ministry of Defence\u2019s [[Future of the Royal Air Force#Combat Air Strategy and Team Tempest|Combat Air Strategy]], the programme for the eventual replacement of the [[Eurofighter Typhoon]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brooke-Holland|first=Louisa|date=2018-05-15|title=Prospects for combat air: What follows Typhoon and Lightning?|url=https://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-8304 | website=UK Parliament }}</ref> He has become one of the leading parliamentary speakers on the Armed Forces, with a particular specialisation in the [[Royal Air Force]]. Courts represents [[RAF Brize Norton]], the largest RAF base in the UK, and serves as the Vice Chair (RAF) of the All-Party Parliamentary Group for the Armed Forces.\n\nOn 8 May 2019, Courts initiated and led a parliamentary debate on 'Human Rights in West Papua.'<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2019-05-08/debates/01B3C1C1-872A-470F-811A-6F17091FCFFF/WestPapuaHumanRights|title=West Papua: Human Rights - Hansard|website=hansard.parliament.uk|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref> This historic debate was the first time MPs had ever debated [[Western New Guinea|West Papua]] in the House of Commons.\n\nAs Chair of the All-Party Parliamentary Group for Small and Micro Business, Courts has been a leading parliamentary campaigner for the interests of small businesses. Courts has consistently protested against the increasing bureaucracy and red tape facing small firms, and called for a full review of the business rates system.\n\nCourts is known for his small state, [[Libertarianism|libertarian]] leanings and identifies with the [[Austrian School|Austrian School of Economics]].\n\nRegarding parliamentary procedure, Courts has been an outspoken critic of [[Early day motion|Early Day Motions]] (EDMs), describing them as \"parliamentary graffiti.\" Courts has said that EDMs are generally tabled by MPs on behalf of \"lobbyists or groups keen to show themselves as doing something\", that they are \"politically impotent\" and a waste of taxpayers' money.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.robertcourts.co.uk/early-day-motions|title=Early Day Motions|website=Robert Courts|language=en|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref>\n\nCourts currently serves on two Parliamentary Select Committees: the Transport Committee, which he was elected to in October 2018, and the Justice Committee, which he joined in January 2019.\n\nIn August 2019, Courts was appointed [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to the Secretary of the State for the Environment, [[Theresa Villiers]].\n\nCourts is a council member of the [[Air League]].<ref>https://www.airleague.co.uk/about-us/key-people/</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCourts lives with his wife and two young children in the village of [[Bladon]]. He is a member of St Martin's Church Parochial Church Council.\n\nHe has been a member of the [[International Churchill Society|Churchill Centre]] for many years, and reviews books about [[Winston Churchill|Churchill]] in the quarterly journal, ''Finest Hour''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://winstonchurchill.org/publications/finest-hour/finest-hour-180/books-arts-curiosities-european-unity/|title=Books, Arts, & Curiosities - European Unity - Finest Hour|date=2018-08-08|website=The International Churchill Society|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref>\n\nCourts is an accomplished blues guitarist and enjoys cycling, swimming, and hiking. He is also a diver, interested in the marine environment; he is a member of the [[Marine Conservation Society]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.robertcourts.co.uk/ Robert Courts official website]\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=robert-courts/4589 |publicwhip=Robert_Courts |theywork=robert_courts}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Cameron]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Witney (UK Parliament constituency)|Witney]]|years=[[2016 Witney by-election|2016]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{South East Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Courts, Robert}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of Lincoln's Inn]]\n[[Category:New Zealand lawyers]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:British barristers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Berkhamsted School]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Sheffield]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Oxfordshire]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Courts"}
{"title_page": "James Cartlidge", "text_new": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = James Cartlidge\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of James Cartlidge MP crop 2.jpg\n| office1 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[South Suffolk (UK Parliament constituency)|South Suffolk]]\n| term_start1 = 7 May 2015\n| term_end1 = \n| predecessor1 = [[Tim Yeo]]\n| successor1 = \n| majority1 = 22,897 (42.8%)\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1974|4|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[London]], [[England]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| spouse = Emily\n| children = 4\n| alma_mater = [[University of Manchester]]\n| website = {{url|jamescartlidge.com|Official website}}\n| caption = Cartlidge in 2019\n}}\n'''James Roger Cartlidge''' (born 30 April 1974) is a [[British people|British]] [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] [[politician]]. He has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[South Suffolk (UK Parliament constituency)|South Suffolk]] since May 2015.\n\n==Early life and education==\nJames Cartlidge was born on 30 April 1974. He was educated at [[Queen Elizabeth's School, Barnet|Queen Elizabeth's School]],<ref name=QES>{{cite web|url=https://www.qebarnet.co.uk/Bringing_an_expert_view_on_housing_to_the_House|title=Bringing an expert view on housing to the House|work=Queen Elizabeth's School, Barnet|accessdate=11 February 2017}}</ref> a state grammar school for boys in the [[market town]] of [[Chipping Barnet]] in north west London, followed by the [[University of Manchester]], where he studied Economics.<ref name=QES/>\n\n==Business career==\nCartlidge's professional background is as an entrepreneur, having founded Share to Buy ltd, a shared ownership property portal, mortgage broker and host of the \u2018London Home Show\u2019, the capital's biggest event for first time buyers.\n\n==Political career==\nCartlidge stood for parliament in [[Lewisham Deptford (UK Parliament constituency)|Lewisham Deptford]] in the 2005 [[2005 United Kingdom general election|general election]] finishing third with 12.4% of the vote. He was also an elected member of [[Babergh District Council elections|Babergh District Council]] before his election to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] in May 2015.\n\nCartlidge fractionally more than doubled majority in the South Suffolk constituency to 17,545 more votes than the next candidate's 10,001 votes, his first election seeing a change in the party of the candidate who finished as runner-up, to the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] and gaining 2,996 votes more than the veteran MP for the seat [[Tim Yeo]] who retired before Cartlidge's election, having been de-selected.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000946 Suffolk South Parliamentary constituency], [[BBC News]]</ref><ref>[http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/james-cartlidge/4519 Biography] UK Parliament website. Accessed 26 May 2015.</ref>\n\nCartlidge has championed South Suffolk produce and one of his first political acts was to bring a barrel of beer from Suffolk into the House of Commons, which he drank with his new parliamentary colleagues.<ref>[http://www.stowmarketmercury.co.uk/news/mps_set_to_slake_their_thirst_with_a_pint_of_sudbury_s_finest_pickwick_bitter_1_4108872 MPs set to slake their thirst with a pint of Sudbury\u2019s finest Pickwick Bitter] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702062323/http://www.stowmarketmercury.co.uk/news/mps_set_to_slake_their_thirst_with_a_pint_of_sudbury_s_finest_pickwick_bitter_1_4108872 |date=2 July 2015 }}, ''Stowmarket Mercury'', 12 June 2015</ref> He also held a South Suffolk Food Day in the House of Commons which featured businesses such as Jimmy's Farm, Suffolk Food Hall and Gifford's Hall Vineyard. The then Secretary of State for the Department of Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, The Rt Hon Elizabeth Truss MP attended the event and spoke to the producers about their businesses.\n\nCartlidge has worked to improve mobile phone signal in the constituency and launched a campaign in Boxford for greater efforts to provide mobile telephone signal in  'not-spots'.<ref name=\"eadt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/boxford_launch_of_petition_to_improve_mobile_phone_signals_in_rural_areas_1_4408474|author=Emma Brennan|title=Boxford launch of petition to improve mobile phone signals in rural areas - Latest Suffolk and Essex News|website=East Anglian Daily Times |date=6 February 2016|accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref> He has taken a train journey from Sudbury to Marks Tey with Rail Executives from Abellio Greater Anglia, Network Rail and the Department for Transport to highlight issues for people travelling by train in the constituency.<ref name=\"suffolkfreepress\">{{cite web|url=http://www.suffolkfreepress.co.uk/news/how-to-avoid-leafgate-this-year-1-7478159|title=How to avoid 'leafgate' this year|website=Suffolk Free Press |date=14 July 2016|accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref><ref>[http://www.stowmarketmercury.co.uk/news/new_mp_james_cartlidge_tackles_railway_issues_between_sudbury_and_marks_tey_1_4078508 New MP James Cartlidge tackles railway issues between Sudbury and Marks Tey] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702070201/http://www.stowmarketmercury.co.uk/news/new_mp_james_cartlidge_tackles_railway_issues_between_sudbury_and_marks_tey_1_4078508 |date=2 July 2015 }}, ''Stowmarket Mercury'', 19 May 2015</ref>\n\nCartlidge was elected to the Public Accounts Commission in November 2015 and the Work and Pensions Committee in October 2016.<ref name=\"parliament\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/james-cartlidge/4519|title=James Cartlidge MP - UK Parliament|website=parliament.uk|accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nCartlidge was opposed to Brexit prior to the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum]].<ref name=\"thespectatorwhichtorympsbackbrexit\">{{cite news|last1=Goodenough|first1=Tom|title=Which Tory MPs back Brexit, who doesn't and who is still on the fence?|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/which-tory-mps-back-brexit-who-doesnt-and-who-is-still-on-the-fence/|accessdate=11 October 2016|work=The Spectator|date=16 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018 he was appointed as PPS to the Health Secretary [[Jeremy Hunt]], and remained his PPS when Hunt was promoted as Foreign Secretary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jamescartlidge.com/news/james-appointed-pps-jeremy-hunt|title=James appointed PPS to Jeremy Hunt|website=James Cartlidge|language=en|access-date=2018-09-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/james-cartlidge-ppc-to-jeremy-hunt-1-5678994|title=New job for Suffolk MP James Cartlidge as aide to Jeremy Hunt at FCO|last=Geater|first=Paul|work=East Anglian Daily Times|access-date=2018-09-30|language=en}}</ref> In August 2019 he was appointed as PPS to the Defence Secretary [[Ben Wallace (politician)]].\n\nIn 2019 Cartlidge was one of only 73 MPs to vote against equal marriage in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wakefield |first1=Lily |title=Here's how every MP voted on equal marriage in Northern Ireland |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2019/07/09/heres-how-every-mp-voted-on-equal-marriage-in-northern-ireland/ |website=Pink News |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=9 July 2019}}</ref> He has publicly expressed his strong support for equal marriage but voted against imposing this law in Northern Ireland 'in absentia'.<ref>https://www.jamescartlidge.com/news/equal-marriage-northern-ireland</ref>\n\nCartlidge is the Patron of the Shotley Pier Project. This community project is working to restored the Victorian pier on the Shotley Pier.<ref>https://www.ipswichstar.co.uk/news/shotely-pier-group-welcomes-patron-south-suffolk-mp-james-cartlidge-1-5362294</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCartlidge is married to Emily, with whom he has four children. His father-in-law is the former Conservative MP, [[Gerald Howarth]], Member of Parliament for [[Aldershot (UK Parliament constituency)|Aldershot]] until 2017.<ref name=\"parliament2\">{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmhansrd/cm150601/debtext/150601-0002.htm|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 01 Jun 2015 (pt 0002)|website=publications.parliament.uk |accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=james-cartlidge/4519 |publicwhip=James_Cartlidge |theywork=james_cartlidge}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tim Yeo]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[South Suffolk (UK Parliament constituency)|South Suffolk]]|years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{East of England Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cartlidge, James}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = James Cartlidge\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of James Cartlidge MP crop 2.jpg\n| office1 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[South Suffolk (UK Parliament constituency)|South Suffolk]]\n| term_start1 = 7 May 2015\n| term_end1 = \n| predecessor1 = [[Tim Yeo]]\n| successor1 = \n| majority1 = 22,897 (42.8%)\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1974|4|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[London]], [[England]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| spouse = Emily\n| children = 4\n| alma_mater = [[University of Manchester]]\n| website = {{url|jamescartlidge.com|Official website}}\n| caption = Cartlidge in 2019\n}}\n'''James Roger Cartlidge''' (born 30 April 1974) is a [[British people|British]] [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] [[politician]]. He has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[South Suffolk (UK Parliament constituency)|South Suffolk]] since May 2015.\n\n==Early life and education==\nJames Cartlidge was born on 30 April 1974. He was educated at [[Queen Elizabeth's School, Barnet|Queen Elizabeth's School]],<ref name=QES>{{cite web|url=https://www.qebarnet.co.uk/Bringing_an_expert_view_on_housing_to_the_House|title=Bringing an expert view on housing to the House|work=Queen Elizabeth's School, Barnet|accessdate=11 February 2017}}</ref> a state grammar school for boys in the [[market town]] of [[Chipping Barnet]] in north west London, followed by the [[University of Manchester]], where he studied Economics.<ref name=QES/>\n\n==Business career==\nCartlidge's professional background is as an entrepreneur, having founded Share to Buy ltd, a shared ownership property portal, mortgage broker and host of the \u2018London Home Show\u2019, the capital\u2019s biggest event for first time buyers.\n\n==Political career==\nCartlidge stood for parliament in [[Lewisham Deptford (UK Parliament constituency)|Lewisham Deptford]] in the 2005 [[2005 United Kingdom general election|general election]] finishing third with 12.4% of the vote. He was also an elected member of [[Babergh District Council elections|Babergh District Council]] before his election to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] in May 2015.\n\nCartlidge fractionally more than doubled majority in the South Suffolk constituency to 17,545 more votes than the next candidate's 10,001 votes, his first election seeing a change in the party of the candidate who finished as runner-up, to the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] and gaining 2,996 votes more than the veteran MP for the seat [[Tim Yeo]] who retired before Cartlidge's election, having been de-selected.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000946 Suffolk South Parliamentary constituency], [[BBC News]]</ref><ref>[http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/james-cartlidge/4519 Biography] UK Parliament website. Accessed 26 May 2015.</ref>\n\nCartlidge has championed South Suffolk produce and one of his first political acts was to bring a barrel of beer from Suffolk into the House of Commons, which he drank with his new parliamentary colleagues.<ref>[http://www.stowmarketmercury.co.uk/news/mps_set_to_slake_their_thirst_with_a_pint_of_sudbury_s_finest_pickwick_bitter_1_4108872 MPs set to slake their thirst with a pint of Sudbury\u2019s finest Pickwick Bitter] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702062323/http://www.stowmarketmercury.co.uk/news/mps_set_to_slake_their_thirst_with_a_pint_of_sudbury_s_finest_pickwick_bitter_1_4108872 |date=2 July 2015 }}, ''Stowmarket Mercury'', 12 June 2015</ref> He also held a South Suffolk Food Day in the House of Commons which featured businesses such as Jimmy\u2019s Farm, Suffolk Food Hall and Gifford\u2019s Hall Vineyard. The then Secretary of State for the Department of Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, The Rt Hon Elizabeth Truss MP attended the event and spoke to the producers about their businesses.\n\nCartlidge has worked to improve mobile phone signal in the constituency and launched a campaign in Boxford for greater efforts to provide mobile telephone signal in  'not-spots'.<ref name=\"eadt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/boxford_launch_of_petition_to_improve_mobile_phone_signals_in_rural_areas_1_4408474|author=Emma Brennan|title=Boxford launch of petition to improve mobile phone signals in rural areas - Latest Suffolk and Essex News|website=East Anglian Daily Times |date=6 February 2016|accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref> He has taken a train journey from Sudbury to Marks Tey with Rail Executives from Abellio Greater Anglia, Network Rail and the Department for Transport to highlight issues for people travelling by train in the constituency.<ref name=\"suffolkfreepress\">{{cite web|url=http://www.suffolkfreepress.co.uk/news/how-to-avoid-leafgate-this-year-1-7478159|title=How to avoid 'leafgate' this year|website=Suffolk Free Press |date=14 July 2016|accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref><ref>[http://www.stowmarketmercury.co.uk/news/new_mp_james_cartlidge_tackles_railway_issues_between_sudbury_and_marks_tey_1_4078508 New MP James Cartlidge tackles railway issues between Sudbury and Marks Tey] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702070201/http://www.stowmarketmercury.co.uk/news/new_mp_james_cartlidge_tackles_railway_issues_between_sudbury_and_marks_tey_1_4078508 |date=2 July 2015 }}, ''Stowmarket Mercury'', 19 May 2015</ref>\n\nCartlidge was elected to the Public Accounts Commission in November 2015 and the Work and Pensions Committee in October 2016.<ref name=\"parliament\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/james-cartlidge/4519|title=James Cartlidge MP - UK Parliament|website=parliament.uk|accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nCartlidge was opposed to Brexit prior to the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum]].<ref name=\"thespectatorwhichtorympsbackbrexit\">{{cite news|last1=Goodenough|first1=Tom|title=Which Tory MPs back Brexit, who doesn't and who is still on the fence?|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/which-tory-mps-back-brexit-who-doesnt-and-who-is-still-on-the-fence/|accessdate=11 October 2016|work=The Spectator|date=16 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018 he was appointed as PPS to the Health Secretary [[Jeremy Hunt]], and remained his PPS when Hunt was promoted as Foreign Secretary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jamescartlidge.com/news/james-appointed-pps-jeremy-hunt|title=James appointed PPS to Jeremy Hunt|website=James Cartlidge|language=en|access-date=2018-09-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/james-cartlidge-ppc-to-jeremy-hunt-1-5678994|title=New job for Suffolk MP James Cartlidge as aide to Jeremy Hunt at FCO|last=Geater|first=Paul|work=East Anglian Daily Times|access-date=2018-09-30|language=en}}</ref> In August 2019 he was appointed as PPS to the Defence Secretary [[Ben Wallace (politician)]].\n\nIn 2019 Cartlidge was one of only 73 MPs to vote against equal marriage in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wakefield |first1=Lily |title=Here's how every MP voted on equal marriage in Northern Ireland |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2019/07/09/heres-how-every-mp-voted-on-equal-marriage-in-northern-ireland/ |website=Pink News |accessdate=9 July 2019 |date=9 July 2019}}</ref> He has publicly expressed his strong support for equal marriage but voted against imposing this law in Northern Ireland 'in absentia'.<ref>https://www.jamescartlidge.com/news/equal-marriage-northern-ireland</ref>\n\nCartlidge is the Patron of the Shotley Pier Project. This community project is working to restored the Victorian pier on the Shotley Pier.<ref>https://www.ipswichstar.co.uk/news/shotely-pier-group-welcomes-patron-south-suffolk-mp-james-cartlidge-1-5362294</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCartlidge is married to Emily, with whom he has four children. His father-in-law is the former Conservative MP, [[Gerald Howarth]], Member of Parliament for [[Aldershot (UK Parliament constituency)|Aldershot]] until 2017.<ref name=\"parliament2\">{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmhansrd/cm150601/debtext/150601-0002.htm|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 01 Jun 2015 (pt 0002)|website=publications.parliament.uk |accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=james-cartlidge/4519 |publicwhip=James_Cartlidge |theywork=james_cartlidge}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tim Yeo]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[South Suffolk (UK Parliament constituency)|South Suffolk]]|years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{East of England Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cartlidge, James}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Cartlidge"}
